{"parentUuid":"e0c8b5bf-2bae-4c1c-8b39-11d5c7c6d9a8","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"74ab6cc1-259e-4f35-896b-31737bc09d28","agentId":"a8eaafaa5ba8f955e","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01DQkE8exXUum8AUdNLr8Dan","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# ROUTER ARCHITECTURE BLUEPRINT\n     2→## DHARMA SWARM — Layer 2 Intelligent Routing Subsystem\n     3→\n     4→**Version:** 1.0  \n     5→**Date:** 2026-03-09  \n     6→**Author:** DHARMA SWARM Architecture Team  \n     7→**Status:** AUTHORITATIVE DESIGN DOCUMENT\n     8→\n     9→---\n    10→\n    11→## Table of Contents\n    12→\n    13→1. [System Overview](#1-system-overview)\n    14→2. [Control Plane Architecture](#2-control-plane-architecture)\n    15→3. [Data Plane Architecture](#3-data-plane-architecture)\n    16→4. [Component Specifications](#4-component-specifications)\n    17→5. [Failure-Path Diagrams](#5-failure-path-diagrams)\n    18→6. [Novel Routing Modes](#6-novel-routing-modes)\n    19→7. [Integration Points](#7-integration-points)\n    20→8. [Technology Stack](#8-technology-stack)\n    21→\n    22→---\n    23→\n    24→## 1. System Overview\n    25→\n    26→### 1.1 What This System Is\n    27→\n    28→The DHARMA SWARM Router is a **provider-agnostic, multi-objective intelligent routing layer** that sits between the orchestrator's Layer 2 (Nervous System / MCP) and the provider ecosystem. Every LLM invocation from every agent in the swarm passes through this router.\n    29→\n    30→The router is not a passthrough proxy. It is an active decision-maker that:\n    31→- Classifies the intent and complexity of every request in <1ms using local heuristics\n    32→- Detects language, context length, and cache state as first-class routing signals\n    33→- Selects the optimal provider×model combination from a live health-ranked pool\n    34→- Manages three-state circuit breakers per provider×model pair\n    35→- Validates outputs and orchestrates escalation for agent callers\n    36→- Writes a tamper-evident audit trail for every routing decision\n    37→\n    38→### 1.2 Two Versions\n    39→\n    40→#### Version A: \"Minimal Elegant\" — 48-Hour MVP\n    41→\n    42→Goal: A production-safe router that eliminates the single worst failure mode (provider outage) while cutting inference costs 40–60% immediately.\n    43→\n    44→**Scope:**\n    45→- Single Python process; in-process state (no Redis)\n    46→- LiteLLM as provider abstraction\n    47→- 7-dimension rule-based complexity scorer (local, <1ms)\n    48→- Static fallback chains per provider (cross-provider principle enforced)\n    49→- Simple health monitor: error-rate circuit breaker, 60s cooldown\n    50→- Synchronous retry with exponential backoff (3 attempts)\n    51→- JSON request/response logs to disk\n    52→- Four provider adapters: Anthropic, OpenAI, OpenRouter, Ollama\n    53→\n    54→**What it does NOT include:**\n    55→- Redis-backed distributed state\n    56→- Contextual bandit online learning\n    57→- Semantic cache tracking\n    58→- Streaming-optimized paths\n    59→- Agent self-score interpreter\n    60→- Canary routing\n    61→\n    62→**48-hour build path:**\n    63→1. Hours 0–8: LiteLLM proxy setup + provider adapters + health monitor\n    64→2. Hours 8–16: Complexity scorer + fallback chain logic + circuit breaker\n    65→3. Hours 16–32: Request/response logging + retry logic + basic telemetry\n    66→4. Hours 32–48: Integration with DHARMA SWARM MCP layer + smoke tests\n    67→\n    68→---\n    69→\n    70→#### Version B: \"Maximal Frontier\" — 90-Day Target\n    71→\n    72→Goal: A self-learning, cache-economics-aware, agent-native routing system that closes within 1–2% of the theoretical Oracle Router on RouterBench.\n    73→\n    74→**Full feature set (all components in Section 4):**\n    75→- Thompson Sampling contextual bandit for online model selection (PILOT architecture, per [arXiv:2508.21141](https://arxiv.org/abs/2508.21141))\n    76→- PROTEUS-style SLA-aware multi-objective scoring (per [arXiv:2601.19402](https://arxiv.org/abs/2601.19402))\n    77→- Cache-state tracker with switching-penalty economics\n    78→- Language detector (FastText lid.176.bin, <0.5ms)\n    79→- Context length analyzer with RULER-calibrated effective-window thresholds\n    80→- Full 5-state health monitor (error rate, p99 latency, TTFT, token throughput, status page)\n    81→- Three-state circuit breaker per provider×model pair stored in Redis\n    82→- Generate-then-verify output verification loop\n    83→- Agent self-score interpreter with escalation logic\n    84→- Canary/shadow traffic controller\n    85→- OpenTelemetry telemetry pipeline to Grafana\n    86→- Tamper-evident hash-chain audit log\n    87→\n    88→**90-day build sequence:**\n    89→- Weeks 1–2: Minimal Elegant + Redis integration + streaming mode\n    90→- Weeks 3–4: Cache state tracker + language detector + context length analyzer\n    91→- Weeks 5–6: Thompson Sampling bandit + PROTEUS scoring layer\n    92→- Weeks 7–8: Agent mode + generate-then-verify + output verifier\n    93→- Weeks 9–10: Canary controller + shadow traffic + A/B experiment framework\n    94→- Weeks 11–12: OpenTelemetry full pipeline + audit log + security hardening\n    95→- Week 13: Load testing, chaos engineering, performance benchmarking\n    96→\n    97→---\n    98→\n    99→### 1.3 Design Principles (from Research)\n   100→\n   101→**Principle 1: Local classification before external dispatch**  \n   102→Complexity scoring via LiteLLM's 7-dimension scorer adds <1ms overhead and zero API calls. Never pay 10–100ms routing latency (à la Not Diamond) for classification you can do locally. ([LiteLLM Docs](https://docs.litellm.ai/docs/routing))\n   103→\n   104→**Principle 2: Cross-provider fallback**  \n   105→The first fallback must always be a different provider, not another model from the same provider. Provider-wide outages (rate limits, infrastructure incidents) create shared failure domains. Mixing Anthropic → OpenAI → Google as fallback tiers provides true independence. ([OpenClaw community principle](https://github.com/BlockRunAI/ClawRouter))\n   106→\n   107→**Principle 3: Cache-economics awareness as a first-class routing signal**  \n   108→For sessions with >10K accumulated tokens, cache hit probability materially affects the true cost of switching models. A mid-session switch from Claude Opus to Sonnet incurs a one-time switching penalty that is typically recouped within 3–5 subsequent calls — but this math must be computed, not assumed. ([Anthropic Prompt Caching docs](https://platform.claude.com/docs/en/build-with-claude/prompt-caching))\n   109→\n   110→**Principle 4: Three-tier resilience — Retry → Fallback → Circuit Breaker**  \n   111→Each layer handles a different failure type. Retries handle transient provider hiccups. Fallback chains handle model/provider unavailability. Circuit breakers prevent retry storms that overwhelm failing providers and protect fallback models from cascade load. All three must coexist. ([Portkey blog](https://portkey.ai/blog/retries-fallbacks-and-circuit-breakers-in-llm-apps))\n   112→\n   113→**Principle 5: Agent mode requires different routing logic**  \n   114→When the caller is an AI agent, latency tolerance is higher, retry is programmatic, and task decomposition allows sub-task-level routing. The canonical pattern is cheap-first → self-score → escalate-only-on-low-confidence. ([Zylos AI research, March 2026](https://zylos.ai/research/2026-03-02-ai-agent-model-routing))\n   115→\n   116→**Principle 6: Effective context length ≠ advertised context length**  \n   117→RULER benchmark data shows that many models claiming 128K context windows degrade severely at 32–64K on complex reasoning. Routing must use empirically verified effective context thresholds, not marketing copy. ([NVIDIA RULER benchmark](https://github.com/NVIDIA/RULER))\n   118→\n   119→**Principle 7: Judge ≠ generator to avoid self-preference bias**  \n   120→NeurIPS 2024 research confirmed that LLM evaluators systematically rate their own outputs higher. The output verifier must be a different model family than the generator. ([NeurIPS 2024 self-preference paper](https://neurips.cc/virtual/2024/poster/96672))\n   121→\n   122→**Principle 8: Multi-objective routing; no single-axis optimization**  \n   123→Single-axis routing (always cheapest, always fastest) leaves performance on the table. The MAGO framework achieves 2.2–3× token efficiency gains by simultaneously optimizing accuracy, efficiency, and calibration. ([MAGO, OpenReview 2026](https://openreview.net/forum?id=i8vZvBFNJg))\n   124→\n   125→---\n   126→\n   127→## 2. Control Plane Architecture\n   128→\n   129→The control plane manages configuration, policy, health state, experiments, and cache state. It operates asynchronously — never in the hot path of a request.\n   130→\n   131→```mermaid\n   132→graph TB\n   133→    subgraph ControlPlane[\"CONTROL PLANE (Async, Out-of-Band)\"]\n   134→        direction TB\n   135→\n   136→        CS[\"📁 Configuration Store\\n(YAML + Redis)\\nModel registry, fallback chains,\\nrouting weights, feature flags\"]\n   137→        PE[\"⚖️ Policy Engine\\nData sovereignty rules,\\nPII routing guards,\\napproval tiers, rate limits\"]\n   138→        HM[\"🏥 Health Monitor\\n5-signal composite score\\nper provider×model\\nCircuit state machine\"]\n   139→        MC[\"📊 Metrics Collector\\nOTel spans, TTFT/p99,\\ncost-per-request,\\ncache hit rates\"]\n   140→        EC[\"🧪 Experiment Controller\\nCanary traffic split,\\nA/B routing, shadow mode,\\nrollback triggers\"]\n   141→        CST[\"🗃️ Cache State Tracker\\nper-session×provider\\ncache warmth, TTL remaining,\\nswitching penalty math\"]\n   142→        BL[\"🎰 Bandit Learner\\nThompson Sampling,\\nonline model scoring,\\nreward signal ingestion\"]\n   143→    end\n   144→\n   145→    subgraph External[\"EXTERNAL SIGNALS\"]\n   146→        SP[\"Provider Status Pages\\n(statuspage.io webhooks)\"]\n   147→        OT[\"OpenTelemetry Collector\\n(Grafana / Prometheus)\"]\n   148→        RP[\"Replay Evaluator\\n(offline eval pipeline)\"]\n   149→    end\n   150→\n   151→    CS -->|policy config| PE\n   152→    CS -->|model list + fallback chains| HM\n   153→    HM -->|circuit state updates| CS\n   154→    MC -->|aggregated metrics| HM\n   155→    MC -->|OTEL spans| OT\n   156→    EC -->|traffic weight updates| CS\n   157→    EC -->|regression gate signals| RP\n   158→    CST -->|cache warmth per session| PE\n   159→    BL -->|updated model weights| CS\n   160→    BL <-->|reward signals| MC\n   161→    SP -->|incident webhooks| HM\n   162→    HM -->|circuit breaker trips| BL\n   163→\n   164→    subgraph DataPlane[\"DATA PLANE (sees control plane outputs)\"]\n   165→        DP[\"Router Data Plane\\n(reads config + health snapshots\\nevery 100ms)\"]\n   166→    end\n   167→\n   168→    CS -->|\"config snapshot (100ms poll)\"| DP\n   169→    PE -->|\"policy decisions (per-request)\"| DP\n   170→    HM -->|\"health snapshot\"| DP\n   171→    CST -->|\"cache state (per-session)\"| DP\n   172→```\n   173→\n   174→### 2.1 Component Roles (Control Plane)\n   175→\n   176→| Component | Responsibility | Update Frequency |\n   177→|-----------|---------------|------------------|\n   178→| **Configuration Store** | Source of truth for model registry, fallback chains, routing weights | On change (hot reload); snapshot cached 100ms |\n   179→| **Policy Engine** | Enforces data sovereignty, PII rules, tier entitlements, rate limits per client | Per-request (reads from cache) |\n   180→| **Health Monitor** | Computes 5-signal composite health score; drives circuit breaker state transitions | Continuous (event-driven on failures); periodic probe in HALF-OPEN |\n   181→| **Metrics Collector** | Aggregates TTFT, p99, cost, cache hits, error rates; feeds bandit and health monitor | Per-request async |\n   182→| **Experiment Controller** | Manages canary splits (0% → 1% → 5% → 10% → 25% → 50% → 100%), A/B routing, shadow mode | Per experiment stage; automated gate checks |\n   183→| **Cache State Tracker** | Per-session, per-provider cache warmth; TTL tracking; switching-penalty calculations | On each request (updates session state) |\n   184→| **Bandit Learner** | Thompson Sampling on (model, context-features) → quality/cost reward; drives routing weight updates | Async after each completed request |\n   185→\n   186→---\n   187→\n   188→## 3. Data Plane Architecture\n   189→\n   190→The data plane is the hot path. Every request flows through it serially. Target overhead: <5ms for the routing decision itself (not including provider latency).\n   191→\n   192→```mermaid\n   193→flowchart TD\n   194→    A[\"🌐 Request Ingestion\\nHTTP/WebSocket/MCP\\nAssign request_id, timestamp\\nClient tier + session_id\"] \n   195→    --> B[\"🔍 Pre-Routing Security Scan\\nRegex injection patterns\\nSemantic PII detector\\nData classification tag\"]\n   196→    --> C[\"🗣️ Language Detector\\nFastText lid.176.bin\\n<0.5ms, 176 languages\\nISO code + confidence + CJK flag\"]\n   197→    --> D[\"🎯 Intent Classifier\\n7-dimension LiteLLM scorer\\n<1ms, zero API calls\\nSIMPLE/MEDIUM/COMPLEX/REASONING\"]\n   198→    --> E[\"📏 Context Length Analyzer\\nToken count + RULER-calibrated\\neffective thresholds\\nContext tier: short/medium/long/very_long\"]\n   199→    --> F[\"💰 Cache-Aware Cost Estimator\\nPer-provider cache warmth lookup\\nSwitching penalty calculation\\nCache-adjusted cost CAC per candidate\"]\n   200→    --> G[\"🏆 Multi-Objective Scorer\\nQuality α + Cost β + Latency γ\\nPareto-optimal selection\\nHard constraints applied\"]\n   201→    --> H[\"🔒 Policy Engine Check\\nData sovereignty filter\\nPII routing guard\\nTier entitlement check\"]\n   202→    --> I[\"🏥 Health Filter\\nCircuit breaker state check\\nFilter OPEN circuits\\nOrder by composite health score\"]\n   203→    --> J[\"⚡ Provider Selection\\nFinal ranked candidate list\\nMode-specific selection logic\\nLog RoutingDecision event\"]\n   204→    --> K[\"📡 Provider Dispatch\\n+Retry/Fallback/Circuit Breaker\\nExponential backoff (3 attempts)\\nFallback chain on exhaustion\"]\n   205→    --> L[\"✅ Response Validation\\nFormat compliance\\nAgent mode: self-score parse\\nSymbolic verifier if code/math\"]\n   206→    --> M[\"📝 Telemetry Pipeline\\nOTel span close\\nBandit reward update\\nCache state update\\nAudit log append\"]\n   207→    --> N[\"🏁 Response Return\\nTo caller (agent or human)\"]\n   208→\n   209→    K -->|\"Circuit trips on failure\"| CB[\"🔴 Circuit Breaker Manager\\nCLOSED → OPEN → HALF-OPEN\\nRedis state, 60s cooldown\\nProbe on HALF-OPEN\"]\n   210→    CB -->|\"Redirect to fallback chain\"| K\n   211→\n   212→    L -->|\"Verification fails\"| EV[\"🔁 Escalation\\nCheap → Expensive model\\nRe-invoke with feedback\\n(Agent mode only, max 2x)\"]\n   213→    EV --> K\n   214→\n   215→    style A fill:#1a3a5c,color:#fff\n   216→    style N fill:#1a5c3a,color:#fff\n   217→    style CB fill:#5c1a1a,color:#fff\n   218→    style EV fill:#5c3a1a,color:#fff\n   219→```\n   220→\n   221→### 3.1 Hot Path Latency Budget\n   222→\n   223→| Stage | Target Latency | Notes |\n   224→|-------|---------------|-------|\n   225→| Request Ingestion | <0.1ms | Assign IDs, parse headers |\n   226→| Pre-Routing Security Scan | <0.5ms | Regex fast path; semantic only if flagged |\n   227→| Language Detector (FastText) | <0.5ms | Local inference, no API call |\n   228→| Intent Classifier (7-dim) | <1ms | Local heuristic, no API call |\n   229→| Context Length Analyzer | <0.2ms | Token count (tiktoken), table lookup |\n   230→| Cache-Aware Cost Estimator | <0.5ms | Redis lookup for cache state, arithmetic |\n   231→| Multi-Objective Scorer | <0.5ms | Weighted sum + Pareto filter |\n   232→| Policy Engine Check | <0.3ms | ABAC rule eval from in-memory cache |\n   233→| Health Filter | <0.3ms | Redis snapshot lookup |\n   234→| Provider Selection | <0.1ms | Top-N from ranked list |\n   235→| **Total routing overhead** | **<4ms** | Before provider dispatch |\n   236→\n   237→---\n   238→\n   239→## 4. Component Specifications\n   240→\n   241→### 4.1 Intent Classifier\n   242→\n   243→**Responsibility:** Classify incoming request into one of four routing tiers (SIMPLE/MEDIUM/COMPLEX/REASONING) using only local heuristics. Zero external API calls. This determines the first-pass model tier.\n   244→\n   245→**Inputs:** Raw message text, message history length, system prompt\n   246→\n   247→**Outputs:** `{tier: \"SIMPLE\"|\"MEDIUM\"|\"COMPLEX\"|\"REASONING\", score: float, signals: dict}`\n   248→\n   249→**Technology Choice:** Implemented as a pure Python heuristic scorer. No model inference. Based on [LiteLLM's complexity-based auto routing (v1.81.14+)](https://docs.litellm.ai/docs/routing), extended with agent-specific signals.\n   250→"}]},"uuid":"1e946525-81a1-4e51-b6f1-bc32909a053d","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:46:30.394Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"e0c8b5bf-2bae-4c1c-8b39-11d5c7c6d9a8","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
