{"parentUuid":"3214aed1-8bcc-411b-a286-1b40fc36cf89","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a8eaafaa5ba8f955e","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"callback"},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_016JTtY3GCkUWWJKAWWLwznF","toolUseID":"toolu_016JTtY3GCkUWWJKAWWLwznF","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:46:31.662Z","uuid":"bb8c33cc-56a5-4f1e-97fc-b35dfd6c9587","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"611dc89a-b2dc-4689-8ebc-66fc1f349c67","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"74ab6cc1-259e-4f35-896b-31737bc09d28","agentId":"a8eaafaa5ba8f955e","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_016JTtY3GCkUWWJKAWWLwznF","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Dharmic Gödel Claw — Recursive Intelligence Research Council Report\n     2→\n     3→**Version:** 1.0  \n     4→**Date:** 2026-03-06  \n     5→**Classification:** Architecture Blueprint — Strategic Research Document  \n     6→**Prepared for:** John Vincent Shrader  \n     7→**Council Composition:** Distributed Systems Architect, AI Systems Researcher, Cognitive Scientist, Software Engineering Researcher, Knowledge Systems Architect, Scientific Methodologist\n     8→\n     9→---\n    10→\n    11→## Table of Contents\n    12→\n    13→1. [Pre-Research Assessment](#1-pre-research-assessment)\n    14→2. [State of the Art: Multi-Agent Orchestration](#2-state-of-the-art-multi-agent-orchestration)\n    15→3. [State of the Art: Artifact Quality & Evaluation](#3-state-of-the-art-artifact-quality--evaluation)\n    16→4. [State of the Art: Knowledge Accumulation](#4-state-of-the-art-knowledge-accumulation)\n    17→5. [State of the Art: Recursive Research Systems](#5-state-of-the-art-recursive-research-systems)\n    18→6. [State of the Art: Tool Protocols & Interoperability](#6-state-of-the-art-tool-protocols--interoperability)\n    19→7. [Council Debate: Disagreements & Tensions](#7-council-debate-disagreements--tensions)\n    20→8. [Proposed Dharmic Gödel Claw Architecture](#8-proposed-dharmic-gödel-claw-architecture)\n    21→9. [Recommended Infrastructure Stack](#9-recommended-infrastructure-stack)\n    22→10. [Risks & Failure Modes](#10-risks--failure-modes)\n    23→11. [Implementation Roadmap](#11-implementation-roadmap)\n    24→12. [Key Technologies to Investigate](#12-key-technologies-to-investigate)\n    25→13. [Potential Breakthroughs](#13-potential-breakthroughs)\n    26→14. [Citations & References](#14-citations--references)\n    27→\n    28→---\n    29→\n    30→## 1. Pre-Research Assessment\n    31→\n    32→### 1.1 The Real Problem\n    33→\n    34→Dharmic Gödel Claw aims to orchestrate multiple AI agents to produce artifacts — research papers, software architectures, verified frameworks — that are genuinely better than what any single agent pass could produce. This is four problems entangled:\n    35→\n    36→**Technical:** Current multi-agent systems produce more output, not better output. Berkeley's MAST study ([arXiv:2503.13657](https://arxiv.org/abs/2503.13657)) found 41-87% task failure rates across 7 major frameworks. 44% of failures stem from system design issues, not LLM limitations. Orchestration overhead frequently degrades quality rather than improving it.\n    37→\n    38→**Epistemic:** A \"Skeptical Critic\" agent running on the same base model as the \"Hypothesis Generator\" shares the same blind spots and hallucination patterns. True epistemic diversity requires fundamentally different reasoning processes, not just different system prompts. Verification loops risk creating theater of rigor rather than actual rigor.\n    39→\n    40→**Architectural:** Recursive self-improvement creates a bootstrapping problem. The evaluator must itself be good at evaluation — and that evaluator must be evaluated. Without grounding in external reality (human judgment, empirical tests, formal verification), the system converges on outputs that satisfy its own metrics while drifting from actual quality.\n    41→\n    42→**Human-AI:** John is the actual source of conceptual novelty in DHARMA. The system needs to amplify his thinking, not replace it. Most agent frameworks assume AI is the primary driver. The real design challenge is a system where contemplative insight and agent capabilities genuinely compound.\n    43→\n    44→### 1.2 What Success Looks Like\n    45→\n    46→**Observable success signals:**\n    47→- A research paper draft that, after editing, gets accepted at a venue like COLM — meeting peer review standards\n    48→- Code artifacts that pass not just unit tests but architectural review\n    49→- Knowledge compounds across sessions: research from week 1 materially improves artifacts in week 4 through structured semantic connections\n    50→- The system surfaces insights John hadn't considered — genuine \"I wouldn't have seen that\" moments\n    51→- Verification catches real errors before they propagate — logical flaws, missing citations, unsupported claims\n    52→\n    53→**Clear failure modes:**\n    54→- Verbose mediocrity: 50-page documents with no ideas a competent researcher couldn't generate in an afternoon\n    55→- Circular validation: agents approve each other's work in a mutual admiration loop\n    56→- Orchestration tax: coordination overhead exceeds value produced\n    57→- Semantic drift: knowledge graph grows but becomes noisy, polluting generation\n    58→- Brittleness: works for one artifact type, can't generalize\n    59→\n    60→### 1.3 Likely Blind Spots\n    61→\n    62→1. **Overreliance on LLM reasoning as ground truth.** The \"Technical Verifier\" checks internal consistency but cannot run experiments, reproduce results, or verify empirical claims against reality.\n    63→2. **The evaluation bottleneck is the real constraint.** Generation is cheap. Knowing whether output is actually good is the hard part — and where current AI is weakest.\n    64→3. **12 agents is likely too many for v1.** Each boundary is a point of information loss. A 4-agent system with better prompts likely outperforms 12 agents. A Jan 2026 paper ([arXiv:2601.04748](https://arxiv.org/html/2601.04748v2)) found single-agent with skills matches multi-agent at 54% fewer tokens.\n    65→4. **\"Recursive self-improvement\" may be a mirage at current capability levels.** The recursion is more likely human-in-the-loop iteration than true machine self-improvement.\n    66→5. **Knowledge graph maintenance is an unsolved problem.** Everyone designs knowledge accumulation; almost no one maintains it well over time.\n    67→6. **DHARMA-specific framing cuts both ways.** Genuine novelty, but concepts like R_V and consciousness metrics have no established benchmarks.\n    68→\n    69→---\n    70→\n    71→## 2. State of the Art: Multi-Agent Orchestration\n    72→\n    73→### 2.1 Framework Landscape (March 2026)\n    74→\n    75→| Framework | Pattern | Best For | Production Readiness | Key Limitation |\n    76→|-----------|---------|----------|---------------------|----------------|\n    77→| **LangGraph** | Cyclic state graph | Iterative refinement, complex branching | High | Boilerplate, graph complexity |\n    78→| **CrewAI** | Role-based hierarchical | Research synthesis, reports | High | No native cycles, implicit state |\n    79→| **AutoGen v0.4** | Actor model | Distributed, code-heavy tasks | High | Migration complexity, GroupChat incoherence |\n    80→| **MetaGPT** | Assembly-line SOP | End-to-end software generation | Medium | Brittle outside software domain |\n    81→| **DSPy** | Pipeline optimizer | Any framework's individual nodes | High | Not orchestration — complements others |\n    82→| **OpenAI Agents SDK** | Handoff graph | Customer support, simple delegation | High | OpenAI-ecosystem-locked |\n    83→| **Google A2A** | Inter-framework protocol | Cross-team agent communication | Growing | Early ecosystem |\n    84→\n    85→Sources: [LangGraph docs](https://www.langchain.com/langgraph), [CrewAI blog](https://www.crewai.com/blog/how-to-build-agentic-systems-the-missing-architecture-for-production-ai-agents), [AutoGen GitHub](https://github.com/microsoft/autogen), [MetaGPT ICLR 2024](https://arxiv.org/abs/2308.00352), [DSPy](https://dspy.ai), [A2A announcement](https://developers.googleblog.com/en/a2a-a-new-era-of-agent-interoperability/)\n    86→\n    87→### 2.2 Critical Evidence\n    88→\n    89→**Failure rates are alarming.** Berkeley's MAST study analyzed 1,642 execution traces across 7 frameworks with expert annotators (Cohen's κ = 0.88). Failure rates: 41-87%. The taxonomy identifies 14 failure modes across 3 categories: system design (44.2%), inter-agent misalignment (32.3%), task verification (23.5%). Most failures are structural, not LLM-related. ([MAST project](https://sky.cs.berkeley.edu/project/mast/))\n    90→\n    91→**Sparse beats dense communication.** All-to-all agent communication is wasteful and misleading. Sparse graph topologies outperform dense debate. Assigning stronger LLMs to higher-centrality nodes yields better outcomes than uniform assignment. ([EMNLP 2024](https://aclanthology.org/2024.findings-emnlp.427.pdf))\n    92→\n    93→**Single-agent with skills can match multi-agent.** A Jan 2026 paper found single-agent with skill libraries matches multi-agent accuracy within 2% while using 54% fewer tokens and 50% less latency — for homogeneous backbone conditions. ([arXiv:2601.04748](https://arxiv.org/html/2601.04748v2))\n    94→\n    95→**Temporal.io is the right execution backbone.** Durable execution, crash recovery, human-in-loop gates, and OpenAI Agents SDK integration now in public preview. For long-running artifact pipelines that must survive crashes and rate limits, Temporal provides the infrastructure layer that LangGraph and CrewAI lack. ([Temporal blog](https://temporal.io/blog/durable-execution-meets-ai-why-temporal-is-the-perfect-foundation-for-ai))\n    96→\n    97→### 2.3 Where Multi-Agent Clearly Wins vs. Loses\n    98→\n    99→**Wins:**\n   100→- Tasks requiring genuinely distinct expertise impossible to encode in a single prompt\n   101→- Long-horizon tasks exceeding single context window\n   102→- Adversarial verification (generate vs. critique)\n   103→- Parallelism-intensive independent subtasks\n   104→- Heterogeneous model capabilities (code + search + vision)\n   105→\n   106→**Loses:**\n   107→- Simple tasks where a well-prompted single model suffices\n   108→- Tasks where information coherence is critical (context fragmentation worse than context length)\n   109→- Real-time applications where latency is unacceptable\n   110→- Budget-constrained systems where token multiplication is prohibitive\n   111→\n   112→---\n   113→\n   114→## 3. State of the Art: Artifact Quality & Evaluation\n   115→\n   116→### 3.1 The Brutal Honest Assessment\n   117→\n   118→Most current LLM evaluation systems are unreliable proxies that degrade under optimization pressure. The field has discovered many failure modes and proposed partial mitigations, but no solved evaluation system exists for open-ended artifacts.\n   119→\n   120→### 3.2 What Actually Works\n   121→\n   122→| Method | Reliability | Applicable To | Key Citation |\n   123→|--------|-------------|---------------|-------------|\n   124→| Execution-based code tests | High | Code | Standard |\n   125→| Citation DOI resolution | High | Research papers | [GPTZero](https://gptzero.me/news/neurips/) |\n   126→| LLM-as-judge (large quality gaps) | Moderate | Any text | [Zheng et al. 2023](https://arxiv.org/abs/2306.05685) |\n   127→| Process Reward Models | Moderate-High | Reasoning chains | [Lightman et al. 2023](https://arxiv.org/abs/2305.20050) |\n   128→| Property-based testing | High | Code invariants | [Agentic PBT](https://arxiv.org/html/2510.09907v1) |\n   129→| Mutation testing | High (quality signal) | Test suites | [MutGen](https://arxiv.org/html/2506.02954v6), [Meta ACH](https://engineering.fb.com/2025/09/30/security/llms-are-the-key-to-mutation-testing-and-better-compliance/) |\n   130→| Multi-judge debate (diverse models) | Moderate | Any text | [ChatEval](https://arxiv.org/abs/2308.07201) |\n   131→\n   132→### 3.3 What Does NOT Work\n   133→\n   134→| Method | Failure Mode | Evidence |\n   135→|--------|-------------|----------|\n   136→| LLM self-evaluation of factual accuracy | Sycophancy, confident wrongness | [arXiv:2601.15436](https://arxiv.org/html/2601.15436v1) |\n   137→| Automated peer review for significance | Conservative bias, misses major flaws | [Nature 2025](https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-025-00894-7) |\n   138→| AI novelty validation | Surface vs. conceptual novelty confusion | [Beel et al.](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.14297) |\n   139→| Self-refinement without grounding | Degrades factual quality over iterations | Multiple studies |\n   140→| Single-metric evaluation | Weakly correlated dimensions | [RewardBench](https://arxiv.org/abs/2403.13787) |\n   141→\n   142→### 3.4 The Hallucinated Citation Crisis\n   143→\n   144→Hallucinated citations in published papers increased from 20 to 275 in one year at ACL/EMNLP venues — a 14x increase. ([arXiv:2601.18724](https://arxiv.org/html/2601.18724v1)). GPTZero found 100 hallucinated citations in NeurIPS 2025 papers. \"Vibe citing\" — LLM-generated citations that amalgamate real sources into plausible but fabricated references — is now a recognized phenomenon.\n   145→\n   146→**Implication for DGC:** Every citation in every artifact must be verified by DOI resolution or URL confirmation. No exceptions.\n   147→\n   148→### 3.5 The 5-Layer Evaluation Architecture\n   149→\n   150→For a recursive artifact factory:\n   151→\n   152→```\n   153→Layer 1 — Automatic Syntactic Checks (always run)\n   154→├── Citation DOI resolution\n   155→├── Code execution + test passing\n   156→├── Format/consistency validation\n   157→└── Semantic similarity against prior versions (regression detection)\n   158→\n   159→Layer 2 — LLM Evaluation with Bias Mitigation\n   160→├── Multi-judge panel (diverse model families)\n   161→├── Role-diverse debate (ChatEval pattern)\n   162→├── G-Eval with mean distributional scoring (not greedy/CoT)\n   163→├── Process-level evaluation (PRM-style)\n   164→└── Length normalization + position randomization\n   165→\n   166→Layer 3 — Adversarial Stress Testing\n   167→├── Targeted red-teaming against claimed novelty\n   168→├── Mutation-based testing (code artifacts)\n   169→├── Cross-validation against existing literature\n   170→└── Reverse-generation consistency check\n   171→\n   172→Layer 4 — Executable Validation (high-stakes only)\n   173→├── Reproduce empirical results\n   174→├── Benchmark claimed algorithms\n   175→├── Property-based tests\n   176→└── Formal verification where applicable\n   177→\n   178→Layer 5 — Human-in-the-Loop (sampled + triggered)\n   179→├── 5-10% random audit\n   180→├── Mandatory for: compounding artifacts, evaluator disagreement\n   181→└── Periodic drift audits (T vs T+30d quality distribution)\n   182→```\n   183→\n   184→### 3.6 The Quality Ratchet\n   185→\n   186→For quality to compound rather than degrade:\n   187→1. Every artifact must pass a minimum quality gate before being used to generate further artifacts\n   188→2. The gate must include at least one Layer 1 or Layer 4 check that cannot be fooled by surface optimization\n   189→3. Regression detection must be automated against a \"golden artifact set\"\n   190→4. Quality gates must tighten over time\n   191→5. Human review of the gates themselves — periodically — because generators eventually find ways to pass gates without achieving underlying quality\n   192→\n   193→---\n   194→\n   195→## 4. State of the Art: Knowledge Accumulation\n   196→\n   197→### 4.1 Core Finding\n   198→\n   199→The central challenge is not retrieval — it is compounding. Most deployed AI memory systems solve retrieval passably; almost none solve accumulation well.\n   200→\n   201→### 4.2 The Four-Layer Architecture\n   202→\n   203→Current state of the art for systems that must compound knowledge over time:\n   204→\n   205→```\n   206→Layer 1: Temporal Knowledge Graph (Neo4j)\n   207→├── Entities, relationships, timestamps\n   208→├── Supersession edges (V2 → V1 with reason)\n   209→├── Confidence scores with temporal decay\n   210→└── Cross-project convergence tracking\n   211→\n   212→Layer 2: Vector Store (Qdrant, self-hosted)\n   213→├── Semantic similarity search\n   214→├── Session/project metadata payloads\n   215→├── HNSW indexing for sub-linear retrieval\n   216→└── Sub-50ms ANN queries\n   217→\n   218→Layer 3: RAPTOR Summary Tree\n   219→├── Recursive abstractive summarization\n   220→├── Multi-level retrieval (leaf → root)\n   221→├── 20% absolute accuracy improvement on complex QA\n   222→└── Rebuild after every 10 new leaf nodes\n   223→\n   224→Layer 4: Provenance Log\n   225→├── PAV ontology: derivedFrom, previousVersion, importedFrom\n   226→├── Every conclusion traceable to source observations\n   227→├── Artifact version control (DVC + MLflow)\n   228→└── \"Negative knowledge\" — failed approaches as first-class artifacts\n   229→```\n   230→\n   231→Sources: [HybridRAG](https://arxiv.org/html/2408.04948v1), [Qdrant + Neo4j integration](https://qdrant.tech/documentation/examples/graphrag-qdrant-neo4j/), [RAPTOR](https://arxiv.org/abs/2401.18059), [PAV ontology](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4177195/)\n   232→\n   233→### 4.3 Agent Memory Benchmarks\n   234→\n   235→The [Mem0 benchmark](https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.19413) is the most rigorous evaluation available:\n   236→\n   237→| System | Single-Hop | Multi-Hop | Temporal | Token Cost |\n   238→|--------|-----------|-----------|----------|------------|\n   239→| Mem0 | 67.13 | 51.15 | 55.51 | 90% lower than full-context |\n   240→| Mem0 (graph) | 65.71 | 47.19 | 58.13 | 85% lower |\n   241→| Zep | 61.70 | 41.35 | 49.31 | High |\n   242→| Full Context | ~70 | ~55 | ~60 | 100% baseline |\n   243→\n   244→Key finding: Mem0 achieves 91% lower latency and 90% lower token cost while maintaining near-competitive quality. For temporal queries (critical for tracking superseded conclusions), graph-enhanced Mem0 outperforms base.\n   245→\n   246→### 4.4 The Staleness Problem\n   247→\n   248→RAG degradation is formally characterized ([arXiv:2506.03100](https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.03100)): there's an intrinsic ceiling, and more retrieved passages past k≈5 actively degrade quality. \"Lost in the Middle\" ([TACL 2024](https://aclanthology.org/2024.tacl-1.9/)) establishes the U-shaped position-bias curve — information in the middle of context windows is systematically ignored.\n   249→\n   250→**Design rules:**"}]},"uuid":"bdfd6a37-79e7-4bfd-9124-1d9e763e354e","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:46:31.662Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"611dc89a-b2dc-4689-8ebc-66fc1f349c67","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
