{"parentUuid":"09d30645-7a9e-4583-a41b-5477a5739c3b","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a8eaafaa5ba8f955e","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"callback"},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_01BUZDt4JTBsX9WV9v5mACUE","toolUseID":"toolu_01BUZDt4JTBsX9WV9v5mACUE","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:46:37.182Z","uuid":"6dffa1a0-4873-484d-be92-e70ffd29fc24","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"47d21f3a-592b-44b0-a05d-19d48e7f6757","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"74ab6cc1-259e-4f35-896b-31737bc09d28","agentId":"a8eaafaa5ba8f955e","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01BUZDt4JTBsX9WV9v5mACUE","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Deep Research: Tool Use, Sandboxes, and MCP for Self-Evolving Swarm Orchestrators\n     2→\n     3→> **Research Date:** March 2026  \n     4→> **Purpose:** Technical reference for building a self-evolving AI swarm orchestrator with \"vast tool use\"  \n     5→> **Scope:** 10 topic areas with concrete implementation details, architecture descriptions, security analysis, and production readiness assessments\n     6→\n     7→---\n     8→\n     9→## Table of Contents\n    10→\n    11→1. [Model Context Protocol (MCP)](#1-model-context-protocol-mcp)\n    12→2. [E2B Code Interpreter SDK](#2-e2b-code-interpreter-sdk)\n    13→3. [Daytona: AI Runtime Infrastructure](#3-daytona-ai-runtime-infrastructure)\n    14→4. [Modal: Serverless Compute for AI](#4-modal-serverless-compute-for-ai)\n    15→5. [OpenAI Codex Agent System](#5-openai-codex-agent-system)\n    16→6. [Browser Automation for Agents](#6-browser-automation-for-agents)\n    17→7. [Code Execution Sandboxes](#7-code-execution-sandboxes)\n    18→8. [Tool Creation and Discovery](#8-tool-creation-and-discovery)\n    19→9. [Filesystem Access Patterns for Agents](#9-filesystem-access-patterns-for-agents)\n    20→10. [API Integration Patterns](#10-api-integration-patterns)\n    21→11. [Synthesis: Architecture for a Swarm Orchestrator with Vast Tool Use](#11-synthesis-architecture-for-a-swarm-orchestrator-with-vast-tool-use)\n    22→\n    23→---\n    24→\n    25→## 1. Model Context Protocol (MCP)\n    26→\n    27→### Overview\n    28→\n    29→The Model Context Protocol (MCP), introduced by Anthropic in November 2024, is an open-source protocol that standardizes how AI applications connect to external data sources and tools. It functions as a \"USB-C of AI integrations\"—a single protocol replacing the dozens of custom integration layers previously needed for each LLM/tool combination. By March 2026, the ecosystem has grown to 5,800+ MCP servers with 97M+ monthly SDK downloads, and has been adopted by Anthropic, OpenAI (Responses API, March 2025), Google (Gemini 2.5 Pro), and Microsoft (Copilot Studio).\n    30→\n    31→**Sources:**  \n    32→- [MCP Architecture Overview](https://modelcontextprotocol.io/docs/learn/architecture)  \n    33→- [MCP Registry Launch](http://blog.modelcontextprotocol.io/posts/2025-09-08-mcp-registry-preview/)  \n    34→- [Enterprise MCP 2026 State](https://www.agilesoftlabs.com/blog/2026/02/how-ai-agents-use-mcp-for-enterprise)\n    35→\n    36→---\n    37→\n    38→### 1.1 Architecture: Hosts, Clients, Servers, Transports\n    39→\n    40→MCP follows a strict layered client-server architecture inspired by the Language Server Protocol (LSP):\n    41→\n    42→```\n    43→┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n    44→│                   MCP HOST                        │\n    45→│  (Claude Desktop, Claude Code, VS Code, ChatGPT)  │\n    46→│                                                   │\n    47→│  ┌──────────────┐   ┌──────────────┐             │\n    48→│  │  MCP Client A│   │  MCP Client B│  ...         │\n    49→│  └──────┬───────┘   └──────┬───────┘             │\n    50→└─────────┼─────────────────┼───────────────────────┘\n    51→          │ (Transport)      │ (Transport)\n    52→    ┌─────▼──────┐    ┌──────▼─────┐\n    53→    │  MCP Server│    │  MCP Server│\n    54→    │  (GitHub)  │    │ (PostgreSQL)│\n    55→    └────────────┘    └────────────┘\n    56→```\n    57→\n    58→**Four key participants:**\n    59→\n    60→| Component | Role |\n    61→|-----------|------|\n    62→| **MCP Host** | The AI application (e.g., Claude Desktop, a custom agent framework). Coordinates one or more MCP Clients. Controls user consent flows and model selection. |\n    63→| **MCP Client** | Embedded in the host. One client per MCP server connection. Manages lifecycle, capability discovery, and request/response routing. |\n    64→| **MCP Server** | Where integration logic lives. Exposes Resources, Tools, Prompts, and Sampling capabilities to connected clients. Can be local (stdio) or remote (HTTP). |\n    65→| **Transport Layer** | Communication channel between client and server. Two mechanisms: Stdio and Streamable HTTP. |\n    66→\n    67→**Two transport mechanisms:**\n    68→\n    69→| Transport | Use Case | Performance | Auth |\n    70→|-----------|----------|-------------|------|\n    71→| **Stdio** | Local process communication (same machine). Server is a child process of the host. | Zero network overhead, optimal latency. | Not required (process-level trust) |\n    72→| **Streamable HTTP** | Remote deployment. HTTP POST for client→server messages; optional Server-Sent Events (SSE) for server→client streaming. | Network-dependent; supports load balancing. | OAuth 2.1 with PKCE (recommended) |\n    73→\n    74→> **Note:** The legacy \"HTTP with SSE\" transport (two separate HTTP connections) is deprecated as of the March 2025 spec revision. All new remote implementations should use Streamable HTTP.\n    75→\n    76→---\n    77→\n    78→### 1.2 Data Layer: JSON-RPC 2.0 Protocol\n    79→\n    80→All MCP communication uses **JSON-RPC 2.0** with three message types: Requests (expect a response), Responses (success or error), and Notifications (one-way, no response needed).\n    81→\n    82→**Initialization Handshake (lifecycle):**\n    83→```json\n    84→// Client → Server: Initialize\n    85→{\n    86→  \"jsonrpc\": \"2.0\",\n    87→  \"id\": 1,\n    88→  \"method\": \"initialize\",\n    89→  \"params\": {\n    90→    \"protocolVersion\": \"2025-11-25\",\n    91→    \"capabilities\": { \"sampling\": {}, \"roots\": {} },\n    92→    \"clientInfo\": { \"name\": \"my-agent\", \"version\": \"1.0\" }\n    93→  }\n    94→}\n    95→\n    96→// Server → Client: Respond with capabilities\n    97→{\n    98→  \"jsonrpc\": \"2.0\",\n    99→  \"id\": 1,\n   100→  \"result\": {\n   101→    \"protocolVersion\": \"2025-11-25\",\n   102→    \"capabilities\": {\n   103→      \"tools\": { \"listChanged\": true },\n   104→      \"resources\": { \"subscribe\": true, \"listChanged\": true },\n   105→      \"prompts\": { \"listChanged\": true }\n   106→    }\n   107→  }\n   108→}\n   109→```\n   110→\n   111→---\n   112→\n   113→### 1.3 Four Core Server Primitives\n   114→\n   115→**1. Tools** — Functions the AI model can call (execute actions, call APIs, write files)\n   116→```python\n   117→@mcp.tool()\n   118→def search_database(query: str, limit: int = 10) -> list[dict]:\n   119→    \"\"\"Search the database for records matching the query.\"\"\"\n   120→    return db.execute(query, limit=limit)\n   121→```\n   122→\n   123→**2. Resources** — URI-addressable data the AI can read (files, database records, API responses)\n   124→```\n   125→postgres://localhost/sales/customers/{customer_id}\n   126→file:///workspace/docs/{filename}\n   127→https://api.example.com/data/{endpoint}\n   128→```\n   129→\n   130→**3. Prompts** — Pre-structured workflow templates or reusable instructions with variables\n   131→```python\n   132→@mcp.prompt()\n   133→def code_review_prompt(pr_number: int) -> list[Message]:\n   134→    return [{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": f\"Review PR #{pr_number} for security issues...\"}]\n   135→```\n   136→\n   137→**4. Sampling** — Allows MCP servers to request LLM completions through the host (enables *agentic servers*)\n   138→```json\n   139→{\n   140→  \"method\": \"sampling/createMessage\",\n   141→  \"params\": {\n   142→    \"messages\": [{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": \"Analyze this error: ...\"}],\n   143→    \"maxTokens\": 1024\n   144→  }\n   145→}\n   146→```\n   147→\n   148→**Additionally:** *Elicitation* allows servers to request additional information from the user (human-in-the-loop), and *Roots* allows servers to inquire about URI/filesystem boundaries.\n   149→\n   150→---\n   151→\n   152→### 1.4 Authentication: OAuth 2.1\n   153→\n   154→Remote MCP servers use **OAuth 2.1 with mandatory PKCE** (Proof Key for Code Exchange):\n   155→\n   156→```\n   157→┌──────────┐    1. Auth Request+PKCE    ┌──────────────┐\n   158→│MCP Client│ ─────────────────────────> │  Auth Server │\n   159→│          │ <─────────────────────────  │  (e.g.Auth0) │\n   160→│          │    2. Auth Code             └──────────────┘\n   161→│          │    3. Code + Verifier ──────────────────┐\n   162→│          │ <─────────────────────────              │\n   163→│          │    4. Access Token (JWT)                │\n   164→│          │                                         ▼\n   165→│          │    5. API Request + Bearer    ┌──────────────┐\n   166→│          │ ─────────────────────────>   │  MCP Server  │\n   167→│          │ <─────────────────────────   │ (Resource)   │\n   168→│          │    6. Resources/Tools         └──────────────┘\n   169→└──────────┘\n   170→```\n   171→\n   172→Key features:\n   173→- **Resource indicators** scope tokens to specific servers (token for Server A can't access Server B)\n   174→- **Short-lived tokens** (15-60 minutes recommended)\n   175→- **Dynamic Client Registration** (RFC 7591) for automatic client onboarding\n   176→- **Automatic endpoint discovery** via RFC 8414 metadata URLs\n   177→\n   178→**Security warning:** The MCP spec makes authorization OPTIONAL. Bitsight research found ~1,000 exposed MCP servers with no authorization whatsoever. Always implement auth for remote deployments. ([Bitsight Security Research](https://www.bitsight.com/blog/exposed-mcp-servers-reveal-new-ai-vulnerabilities))\n   179→\n   180→---\n   181→\n   182→### 1.5 Ecosystem State (2025-2026)\n   183→\n   184→| Metric | Value |\n   185→|--------|-------|\n   186→| Total MCP servers | 5,800+ (Dec 2025 registry), 36,039 on GitHub |\n   187→| Monthly SDK downloads | 97M+ |\n   188→| MCP clients supporting protocol | 300+ |\n   189→| Deployment split | 86% local (stdio) / 14% remote (HTTP growing 4x since May 2025) |\n   190→| Major adopters | Anthropic, OpenAI, Google, Microsoft, Block (Square), Bloomberg, Apollo |\n   191→\n   192→**Popular production MCP servers:**\n   193→- **GitHub** — Repository search, PR management, issue tracking\n   194→- **PostgreSQL** — Schema inspection, read-only queries\n   195→- **Slack** — Channel history, message posting\n   196→- **Google Drive** — File search, document reading\n   197→- **Salesforce** — CRM operations\n   198→- **Snowflake** — Data warehouse queries\n   199→- **Jira/Linear** — Project management\n   200→"}]},"uuid":"40ea52c2-fb56-4e9f-9288-1bbd682f671e","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:46:37.181Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"47d21f3a-592b-44b0-a05d-19d48e7f6757","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
