{"parentUuid":"5dc0d3b7-c901-4e3f-940c-48e94e38316b","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a8eaafaa5ba8f955e","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"bash \"${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/scripts/hooks/run-with-flags-shell.sh\" \"post:observe\" \"skills/continuous-learning-v2/hooks/observe.sh\" \"standard,strict\""},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_0147KNoLyYG1MRhbqgaBT4RB","toolUseID":"toolu_0147KNoLyYG1MRhbqgaBT4RB","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:46:37.614Z","uuid":"9434ea97-ef9e-4f0f-9ea5-4142c78c0583","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"9434ea97-ef9e-4f0f-9ea5-4142c78c0583","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a8eaafaa5ba8f955e","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"callback"},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_0147KNoLyYG1MRhbqgaBT4RB","toolUseID":"toolu_0147KNoLyYG1MRhbqgaBT4RB","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:46:37.614Z","uuid":"836d3f01-32a8-4512-bb19-9be6bcea93b6","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"83e36ce4-bbed-4cb2-89b9-7d4024ec5a4e","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"74ab6cc1-259e-4f35-896b-31737bc09d28","agentId":"a8eaafaa5ba8f955e","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0147KNoLyYG1MRhbqgaBT4RB","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# DHARMA SWARM Memory Palace: Architectural Research Domains 1–3\n     2→\n     3→**Research Date:** 2026-03-09  \n     4→**Scope:** DHARMA SWARM agent-native PKM on 4GB RAM Ubuntu VPS, plain-text markdown + git, $50–500/month, EN/JP/Sanskrit multilingual, ~500 notes → 10K+, AI agent as primary user.\n     5→\n     6→---\n     7→\n     8→## DOMAIN 1: SEMANTIC RETRIEVAL ARCHITECTURE\n     9→\n    10→### 1.1 State of the Art (2026)\n    11→\n    12→#### Embedding Models: Comprehensive Benchmark Matrix\n    13→\n    14→The 2026 landscape for multilingual embedding has converged on a clear tier structure. Sanskrit is the critical differentiator that eliminates most \"multilingual\" models.\n    15→\n    16→| Model | Dims | Max Tokens | MIRACL NDCG@10 | BEIR | Japanese Support | Sanskrit | Model Size fp16 | Type |\n    17→|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n    18→| **BGE-M3** (BAAI) | 1024 | 8192 | **69.2** | 48.8 | ✅ | ✅ via multilingual | **1.06 GB** | Local |\n    19→| **multilingual-e5-large** | 1024 | 514 | 66.5 | 51.4 | ✅ | ⚠️ limited | ~0.56 GB | Local |\n    20→| **Nomic Embed v2 MoE** | 768 (flex) | 512 | **65.8** | 52.8 | ✅ | ✅ (100+ langs) | ~0.6 GB active | Local |\n    21→| **Cohere Embed v4** | 1024 | 128K | JP: 78.4 | 47.3 | ✅ | ❌ not listed | API only | API |\n    22→| **voyage-multilingual-2** | 1024 | 32K | avg 5.6% > others | N/A | ✅ | ⚠️ unclear | API only | API |\n    23→| Arctic Embed v2 Large | 1024 | — | 66.0 | 55.65 | ✅ | — | ~1.1 GB | Local |\n    24→| OpenAI text-embedding-3-large | 3072 | — | 79.5 avg (MIRACL subset) | — | ✅ | ❌ | API | API |\n    25→\n    26→**Sources:**\n    27→- Nomic Embed v2 MoE card: https://huggingface.co/nomic-ai/nomic-embed-text-v2-moe\n    28→- BGE-M3 memory: https://huggingface.co/BAAI/bge-m3/discussions/64\n    29→- Cohere Embed v4 MIRACL breakdown: https://ai.azure.com/catalog/models/embed-v-4-0\n    30→- Voyage multilingual-2 blog: https://blog.voyageai.com/2024/06/10/voyage-multilingual-2-multilingual-embedding-model/\n    31→\n    32→**Sanskrit-specific note:** SpaCy has a Sanskrit language class (`sa`) but zero trained packages. BGE-M3 covers 100+ languages and handles Devanagari script. A 2025 paper (EMNLP) showed \"Monolingual Adapter Networks\" can improve Sanskrit embedding alignment with English pivot using the Itihasa corpus: https://aclanthology.org/2025.mrl-main.24.pdf\n    33→\n    34→**Key insight on BGE-M3:** BGE-M3 is unique in supporting three retrieval modes simultaneously from one model:\n    35→1. **Dense retrieval** (standard embedding similarity)\n    36→2. **Sparse retrieval** (lexical, like BM25 but learned)\n    37→3. **Multi-vector ColBERT-style** (late interaction)\n    38→\n    39→This makes BGE-M3 the only local model that natively enables hybrid dense+sparse retrieval without a separate BM25 index.\n    40→\n    41→#### RAM Footprint at 10K Docs\n    42→\n    43→Assuming 10K notes, average 3 chunks each = **30K chunks** (typical PKM notes split at headers and paragraphs):\n    44→\n    45→| Component | BGE-M3 1024d | nomic-v2 768d | Notes |\n    46→|---|---|---|---|\n    47→| Vector storage (fp32) | 117 MB | 88 MB | 30K × dims × 4 bytes |\n    48→| HNSW graph (M=16) | 7.3 MB | 7.3 MB | 30K × 16 × 2 × 8 bytes |\n    49→| Index overhead (15%) | 19 MB | 14 MB | |\n    50→| **Total index** | **~143 MB** | **~110 MB** | Disk or memory |\n    51→| Model weights fp16 | 1,060 MB | ~600 MB | RAM resident at runtime |\n    52→| **Total RAM peak** | **~1.2 GB** | **~0.71 GB** | Model + working index |\n    53→\n    54→At 10K notes, the entire retrieval system fits in **≤ 1.5 GB RAM** even with BGE-M3, leaving 2.5 GB for the rest of the stack.\n    55→\n    56→**LanceDB disk-backed option:** If RAM is tight, LanceDB stores vectors on disk using Apache Arrow column format. Memory-mapped access with IVF-PQ achieves >0.90 recall@1 at ~3ms query latency on NVMe SSD. At 10K docs (30K chunks, 1024d fp32 = 117MB), the entire index fits in the OS page cache anyway.\n    57→\n    58→---\n    59→\n    60→#### Hybrid Search: BM25 + Vector + Metadata Filtering\n    61→\n    62→Hybrid search combines BM25 lexical matching with dense vector similarity, then fuses rankings using **Reciprocal Rank Fusion (RRF)**:\n    63→\n    64→```\n    65→hybrid_score(d) = α × BM25_rank_score(d) + (1-α) × vector_rank_score(d)\n    66→```\n    67→\n    68→**For markdown files on 4GB RAM, the practical pattern is:**\n    69→\n    70→1. **BM25 via SQLite FTS5** (zero additional memory, built-in to Python's sqlite3)\n    71→2. **Vector index via LanceDB or sqlite-vec** (disk-backed, low RAM)\n    72→3. **Metadata filter** on YAML frontmatter fields (tags, date, belief_confidence)\n    73→4. **RRF fusion** in Python\n    74→\n    75→```python\n    76→# SQLite FTS5 for BM25 on markdown\n    77→import sqlite3\n    78→\n    79→conn = sqlite3.connect(\"pkm.db\")\n    80→conn.execute(\"CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE notes_fts USING fts5(content, path, tags)\")\n    81→\n    82→# BM25 search (SQLite FTS5 uses BM25 by default with rank)\n    83→results_bm25 = conn.execute(\n    84→    \"SELECT path, rank FROM notes_fts WHERE notes_fts MATCH ? ORDER BY rank LIMIT 50\",\n    85→    (query,)\n    86→).fetchall()\n    87→\n    88→# Then fuse with vector results via RRF\n    89→def reciprocal_rank_fusion(results_bm25, results_vector, k=60):\n    90→    scores = {}\n    91→    for rank, (doc_id, _) in enumerate(results_bm25):\n    92→        scores[doc_id] = scores.get(doc_id, 0) + 1/(k + rank + 1)\n    93→    for rank, (doc_id, _) in enumerate(results_vector):\n    94→        scores[doc_id] = scores.get(doc_id, 0) + 1/(k + rank + 1)\n    95→    return sorted(scores.items(), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)\n    96→```\n    97→\n    98→**sqlite-vec** (https://alexgarcia.xyz/sqlite-vec/) is a SQLite extension enabling KNN vector search directly inside SQLite using `vec0` virtual tables. Example:\n    99→\n   100→```sql\n   101→CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE vec_notes USING vec0(embedding float[1024]);\n   102→INSERT INTO vec_notes(rowid, embedding) VALUES (?, ?);\n   103→SELECT rowid, distance FROM vec_notes\n   104→  WHERE embedding MATCH ? ORDER BY distance LIMIT 20;\n   105→```\n   106→\n   107→This allows combining FTS5 BM25 + vec0 vector search in a single SQLite database — the lowest-friction hybrid implementation for a markdown PKM.\n   108→\n   109→**References:**\n   110→- SQLite-vec features: https://alexgarcia.xyz/sqlite-vec/features/vec0.html#metadata\n   111→- Hybrid search RRF guide: https://oneuptime.com/blog/post/2026-01-30-hybrid-search/view\n   112→\n   113→---\n   114→\n   115→#### Chunking Strategies for PKM Markdown Notes\n   116→\n   117→PKM notes (50–500 lines, 200–3000 words) have distinct structure: YAML frontmatter, ## headers, body prose, code blocks, wikilinks. The optimal strategy differs from academic PDFs.\n   118→\n   119→**2026 benchmark findings** from 7-strategy comparison on RAG systems:\n   120→\n   121→| Strategy | Accuracy | Doc F1 | Notes |\n   122→|---|---|---|---|\n   123→| RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter 512 | **69%** | 0.77 | Best overall |\n   124→| Fixed-size 512 | 67% | 0.75 | Solid baseline |\n   125→| Semantic chunking | 54% | 0.42 | Over-fragments, bad for PKM |\n   126→| Page-per-chunk | 57% | **0.88** | Doc coverage, not precision |\n   127→| Proposition chunking | ~60% | low | Groundedness only |\n   128→\n   129→Source: https://www.reddit.com/r/Rag/comments/1r47duk/we_benchmarked_7_chunking_strategies_most_best/\n   130→\n   131→**Semantic chunking specifically performs poorly** for PKM because it generates tiny chunks (avg 43 tokens) that lose the conversational/continuous narrative of personal notes. The 28% improvement figure for semantic chunking (widely cited) applies to formal documents, not informal notes.\n   132→\n   133→**For DHARMA SWARM, the recommended strategy is a custom hybrid:**\n   134→\n   135→```python\n   136→from langchain_text_splitters import MarkdownHeaderTextSplitter, RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter\n   137→\n   138→# Stage 1: Split on markdown headers (preserves structure)\n   139→headers_to_split = [\n   140→    (\"#\", \"h1\"),\n   141→    (\"##\", \"h2\"),\n   142→    (\"###\", \"h3\"),\n   143→]\n   144→md_splitter = MarkdownHeaderTextSplitter(\n   145→    headers_to_split_on=headers_to_split,\n   146→    strip_headers=False  # Keep headers in chunks for context\n   147→)\n   148→\n   149→# Stage 2: Recursively split large sections (>512 tokens)\n   150→char_splitter = RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter(\n   151→    chunk_size=512,\n   152→    chunk_overlap=64,\n   153→    separators=[\"\\n\\n\", \"\\n\", \". \", \" \", \"\"],\n   154→)\n   155→\n   156→def chunk_pkm_note(markdown_text: str, note_path: str) -> list[dict]:\n   157→    \"\"\"Two-stage PKM-aware chunking.\"\"\"\n   158→    # Extract YAML frontmatter first\n   159→    frontmatter, body = extract_frontmatter(markdown_text)\n   160→    \n   161→    # Stage 1: split by headers\n   162→    header_chunks = md_splitter.split_text(body)\n   163→    \n   164→    # Stage 2: recursively split large header sections\n   165→    final_chunks = []\n   166→    for chunk in header_chunks:\n   167→        if len(chunk.page_content.split()) > 350:  # ~512 tokens threshold\n   168→            sub_chunks = char_splitter.split_text(chunk.page_content)\n   169→            for sc in sub_chunks:\n   170→                final_chunks.append({\n   171→                    \"content\": sc,\n   172→                    \"metadata\": {**frontmatter, **chunk.metadata, \"path\": note_path}\n   173→                })\n   174→        else:\n   175→            final_chunks.append({\n   176→                \"content\": chunk.page_content,\n   177→                \"metadata\": {**frontmatter, **chunk.metadata, \"path\": note_path}\n   178→            })\n   179→    return final_chunks\n   180→```\n   181→\n   182→**Rationale for DHARMA SWARM PKM:**\n   183→- Notes ≤ 50 lines: keep whole (no chunking needed, whole note = one vector)\n   184→- Notes 50–200 lines: split at H2/H3 headers\n   185→- Notes > 200 lines: two-stage header + recursive split\n   186→- Always preserve YAML frontmatter metadata in every chunk\n   187→\n   188→---\n   189→\n   190→#### Reranking: Cross-Encoders vs. Late Interaction\n   191→\n   192→| Model | MRR@10 (MS MARCO) | Docs/sec (CPU) | RAM fp16 | Multilingual | Verdict |\n   193→|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n   194→| ms-marco-MiniLM-L6-v2 | 0.390 | 1800 | **44 MB** | ❌ EN only | Best RAM/speed tradeoff |\n   195→| ms-marco-MiniLM-L12-v2 | 0.397 | 960 | 66 MB | ❌ EN only | Slightly better recall |\n   196→| bge-reranker-v2-m3 | higher (multilingual) | ~200 | **1.1 GB** | ✅ 100+ | Best for JP/Sanskrit |\n   197→| DeBERTa-v3-large | 0.425 | 100 (GPU) | 868 MB | ❌ | Too heavy |\n   198→| ColBERT-v2 | competitive | fast ANN | ~210 MB | ❌ EN | Needs precomputation |\n   199→\n   200→Sources:"}]},"uuid":"80d803c9-eacf-4a24-aadb-910eb0187f73","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:46:37.614Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"83e36ce4-bbed-4cb2-89b9-7d4024ec5a4e","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
