{"parentUuid":"e1c4bf74-8ded-4f07-be12-e1b6c2ecd32f","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a8eaafaa5ba8f955e","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"callback"},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_012Js9rfYKsUrfhEZnLcwG28","toolUseID":"toolu_012Js9rfYKsUrfhEZnLcwG28","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:46:41.741Z","uuid":"f50956c3-9bf5-4399-babe-0624e125b8e4","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"f33abff5-1200-4577-a7e4-44bf1280d3c4","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"74ab6cc1-259e-4f35-896b-31737bc09d28","agentId":"a8eaafaa5ba8f955e","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_012Js9rfYKsUrfhEZnLcwG28","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# DHARMA SWARM: Architecture Plan for the Most Advanced Self-Evolving Agentic Orchestrator on Earth\n     2→\n     3→> **Author**: John Vincent Shrader + Perplexity Computer Research Team\n     4→> **Date**: March 3, 2026\n     5→> **Status**: Architecture Blueprint — Ready for Implementation Blitz\n     6→> **Codename**: DHARMA SWARM (Darwin-Heuristic Autonomous Recursive Meta-Agent Swarm)\n     7→\n     8→---\n     9→\n    10→## Executive Summary\n    11→\n    12→This document is the complete architecture plan for building a self-evolving agentic swarm orchestrator that synthesizes the best ideas from every frontier system operating today — Perplexity Computer, Warp Oz, Claude Code Agent Teams, OpenClaw, the Darwin-Gödel Machine, ADAS, Voyager, and more — into a single unified system that:\n    13→\n    14→1. **Orchestrates hundreds of agents simultaneously** with heterogeneous models (open + frontier)\n    15→2. **Maintains deep context** across hundreds of files with near-perfect memory\n    16→3. **Self-evolves** its own workflows, tools, prompts, and orchestration patterns\n    17→4. **Determines its own teleology** from context, files, and user connection\n    18→5. **Runs autonomously for hours** with human-in-the-loop safety rails\n    19→6. **Rewrites its own code** at the scaffold level (not model weights)\n    20→7. **Integrates complex environments** with vast tool use via MCP\n    21→8. **Operates at every level**: sudo/system → meta-orchestration → agent manipulation → code generation → self-rewriting\n    22→\n    23→This is not a toy. This is a production architecture.\n    24→\n    25→---\n    26→\n    27→## Table of Contents\n    28→\n    29→1. [Design Philosophy & Non-Negotiables](#1-design-philosophy)\n    30→2. [Layered Architecture (The Stack)](#2-layered-architecture)\n    31→3. [Layer 0: Substrate — Compute & Sandboxing](#3-layer-0-substrate)\n    32→4. [Layer 1: The Nervous System — MCP + Tool Ecosystem](#4-layer-1-nervous-system)\n    33→5. [Layer 2: Memory Palace — Deep Context & Recall](#5-layer-2-memory-palace)\n    34→6. [Layer 3: The Swarm — Agent Topology & Communication](#6-layer-3-the-swarm)\n    35→7. [Layer 4: The Orchestrator — Teleological Command Layer](#7-layer-4-the-orchestrator)\n    36→8. [Layer 5: The Darwin Engine — Self-Evolution Loop](#8-layer-5-darwin-engine)\n    37→9. [Layer 6: The Dharma Layer — Safety, Ethics, Alignment](#9-layer-6-dharma-layer)\n    38→10. [Model Strategy: Open + Frontier Hybrid](#10-model-strategy)\n    39→11. [Teleological Bootstrap: How the System Discovers Its Purpose](#11-teleological-bootstrap)\n    40→12. [Implementation Roadmap](#12-implementation-roadmap)\n    41→13. [Technology Stack Decisions](#13-technology-stack)\n    42→14. [Risk Analysis & Mitigations](#14-risk-analysis)\n    43→15. [References & Sources](#15-references)\n    44→\n    45→---\n    46→\n    47→## 1. Design Philosophy & Non-Negotiables {#1-design-philosophy}\n    48→\n    49→### Core Principles\n    50→\n    51→Drawing from 24 years of Akram Vignan contemplative practice and deep study of recursive self-reference:\n    52→\n    53→1. **Separation of the Knower and the Known**: The meta-level observation layer (Layer 6) NEVER modifies itself. Like pure consciousness observing the intellect, the Dharma Layer watches but does not participate in self-modification. This is the architectural equivalent of the *Gnani* watching the *prakruti*.\n    54→\n    55→2. **Evolution Through Scaffolding, Not Weights**: Following DGM (Sakana AI, 2025), all self-improvement operates on agent code/prompts/workflows — never on model weights. The FM is the *atma* — fixed, pure capability. The scaffolding is the *karma* — mutable, improvable, observable.\n    56→\n    57→3. **Test-Gated Evolution**: Every self-modification must pass through empirical validation before promotion. No change is accepted on faith. The test suite is the *Tirthankara's* teaching — objective, reproducible, unfalsifiable.\n    58→\n    59→4. **Radical Transparency**: Every agent action, every self-modification, every decision is logged in a complete audit trail (the Archive). The system cannot hide from itself or from its operator.\n    60→\n    61→5. **Graceful Degradation**: If any layer fails, the system drops to the next lower level of capability. If the Darwin Engine crashes, the swarm continues operating on its last-known-good configuration. If the swarm fails, the orchestrator falls back to single-agent mode.\n    62→\n    63→6. **Heterogeneous Intelligence**: No single model does everything. Use the cheapest model that can handle each task. Route complex reasoning to frontier models, routine tasks to open models, code generation to specialized models.\n    64→\n    65→### Non-Negotiables\n    66→\n    67→| Principle | Implementation |\n    68→|-----------|---------------|\n    69→| Human veto power | Any operation can be halted by human at any time; kill switch is external to the system |\n    70→| Git as ground truth | All code, all configs, all prompts versioned in git; any state can be rolled back |\n    71→| Sandbox everything | No agent ever executes on bare metal; Firecracker microVMs or Docker with seccomp |\n    72→| Cost guardrails | Per-agent and per-session token budgets; automatic model cascade on budget exhaustion |\n    73→| No weight modification | FM weights are read-only; self-improvement is scaffold-only |\n    74→| Archive everything | Complete genealogy of every self-modification, every agent spawn, every tool call |\n    75→\n    76→---\n    77→\n    78→## 2. Layered Architecture (The Stack) {#2-layered-architecture}\n    79→\n    80→```\n    81→┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n    82→│  LAYER 6: DHARMA LAYER (Safety / Ethics / Alignment)             │\n    83→│  • Invariant safety rules • Human veto • Kill switch             │\n    84→│  • Dharma Agent (cannot be modified by any other layer)          │\n    85→│  [IMMUTABLE — NEVER SELF-MODIFIES]                               │\n    86→├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n    87→│  LAYER 5: DARWIN ENGINE (Self-Evolution Loop)                     │\n    88→│  • Archive of agent genomes • Evolutionary selection              │\n    89→│  • Mutation via FM • Test-gated promotion • ADAS-style search    │\n    90→│  [MODIFIES LAYERS 1-4 ONLY — NEVER SELF OR LAYER 6]             │\n    91→├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n    92→│  LAYER 4: ORCHESTRATOR (Teleological Command)                     │\n    93→│  • Goal decomposition • Task allocation • Resource budgeting      │\n    94→│  • Teleological bootstrap from context/files/user connection     │\n    95→│  • Orchestration patterns: fan-out, pipeline, mesh, hierarchy    │\n    96→├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n    97→│  LAYER 3: THE SWARM (Agents & Communication)                      │\n    98→│  • Agent pool (5 → 20 → 100s) • Role assignment                  │\n    99→│  • Communication: shared state + mailbox + blackboard             │\n   100→│  • Heterogeneous models: open + frontier per-agent               │\n   101→├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n   102→│  LAYER 2: MEMORY PALACE (Deep Context & Recall)                   │\n   103→│  • MemGPT-style virtual context • Codebase index (AST + embed)  │\n   104→│  • Knowledge graph (Graphiti) • Episodic/semantic/procedural     │\n   105→│  • Recursive summarization • Context compaction                   │\n   106→├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n   107→│  LAYER 1: NERVOUS SYSTEM (MCP + Tools)                            │\n   108→│  • MCP server registry • Dynamic tool discovery/creation          │\n   109→│  • Browser automation • API integrations • File system access    │\n   110→│  • Code execution sandbox                                         │\n   111→├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n   112→│  LAYER 0: SUBSTRATE (Compute & Sandboxing)                        │\n   113→│  • Firecracker microVMs / Docker • GPU access (Modal)            │\n   114→│  • Git-based versioning • Process isolation • Networking          │\n   115→└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n   116→```\n   117→\n   118→### Key Insight: Layers Can Only Modify Downward\n   119→\n   120→This is the critical safety invariant. The Darwin Engine (L5) can modify the Swarm (L3), Orchestrator (L4), Memory (L2), and Tools (L1). But it CANNOT modify itself or the Dharma Layer (L6). The Dharma Layer is read-only from the system's perspective — only the human operator can modify it.\n   121→\n   122→This mirrors DGM's architecture where the outer evolutionary engine is explicitly fixed and unreachable by the agents it evolves.\n   123→\n   124→---\n   125→\n   126→## 3. Layer 0: Substrate — Compute & Sandboxing {#3-layer-0-substrate}\n   127→\n   128→### Compute Architecture\n   129→\n   130→```\n   131→┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n   132→│                    CONTROL PLANE                          │\n   133→│  (Runs on host machine — NOT in sandbox)                 │\n   134→│  • Process supervisor (systemd / PM2)                    │\n   135→│  • Agent lifecycle manager                               │\n   136→│  • Resource allocator                                    │\n   137→│  • Audit logger                                          │\n   138→│  • Kill switch daemon                                    │\n   139→└───────────┬───────────────────────────┬─────────────────┘\n   140→            │                           │\n   141→    ┌───────▼──────┐           ┌───────▼──────┐\n   142→    │ Firecracker  │           │ Firecracker  │  ... × N\n   143→    │ microVM #1   │           │ microVM #2   │\n   144→    │ ┌──────────┐ │           │ ┌──────────┐ │\n   145→    │ │ Agent A  │ │           │ │ Agent B  │ │\n   146→    │ │ + tools  │ │           │ │ + tools  │ │\n   147→    │ └──────────┘ │           │ └──────────┘ │\n   148→    │ 2 vCPU, 512M │           │ 4 vCPU, 2G  │\n   149→    └──────────────┘           └──────────────┘\n   150→```\n   151→\n   152→### Technology Selection\n   153→\n   154→| Component | Choice | Rationale |\n   155→|-----------|--------|-----------|\n   156→| **Agent sandboxes** | Firecracker microVMs (via E2B SDK or self-hosted) | <125ms boot, 5MB memory overhead, KVM-level isolation. Production-proven at AWS Lambda scale. |\n   157→| **GPU workloads** | Modal | Infrastructure-as-Python-code. A100/H100 access. Auto-scaling to 20K+ containers. Perfect for batch inference with open models. |\n   158→| **Local dev** | Docker with gVisor runtime | Faster iteration than Firecracker. gVisor adds syscall interception without full VM overhead. |\n   159→| **Version control** | Git (libgit2 bindings) | Every workspace is a git repo. Every agent commit is atomic. Rollback = `git reset --hard`. Branch-per-agent for parallel work. |\n   160→| **Process management** | Custom Rust supervisor | Low-overhead, handles 100s of child processes, integrates with Firecracker API. Fallback: PM2 for prototype. |\n   161→\n   162→### Resource Budget Model\n   163→\n   164→```python\n   165→@dataclass\n   166→class AgentBudget:\n   167→    max_tokens_per_turn: int = 32_000      # Output token limit per LLM call\n   168→    max_tokens_per_session: int = 2_000_000 # Total token budget for agent lifetime\n   169→    max_wall_time_seconds: int = 3600       # 1 hour max per agent session\n   170→    max_tool_calls: int = 500               # Prevent infinite tool loops\n   171→    max_cost_usd: float = 5.00              # Hard cost cap per agent\n   172→    model_cascade: list[str] = field(default_factory=lambda: [\n   173→        \"claude-sonnet-4\",       # First choice: capable + affordable\n   174→        \"deepseek-v3\",           # Fallback: open model, very capable\n   175→        \"qwen-2.5-72b\",         # Second fallback: strong open model\n   176→        \"llama-3.3-70b\",        # Emergency fallback: fast, cheap\n   177→    ])\n   178→```\n   179→\n   180→When an agent exhausts its budget at one model tier, it automatically cascades to the next cheaper model. This ensures the swarm never halts due to cost — it degrades gracefully.\n   181→\n   182→---\n   183→\n   184→## 4. Layer 1: The Nervous System — MCP + Tool Ecosystem {#4-layer-1-nervous-system}\n   185→\n   186→### MCP as Universal Tool Protocol\n   187→\n   188→MCP (Model Context Protocol) is the standard interface for ALL tool connections. Every tool — file system, browser, API, database, code execution — is exposed as an MCP server. This gives us:\n   189→\n   190→1. **Universal discovery**: Any agent can query the MCP registry to find available tools\n   191→2. **Standardized invocation**: JSON-RPC 2.0 for all tool calls, regardless of underlying implementation\n   192→3. **Dynamic tool creation**: Agents can register NEW MCP servers at runtime (the Voyager pattern)\n   193→4. **Security boundary**: MCP's transport layer enforces auth (OAuth 2.1) and rate limiting\n   194→\n   195→### Tool Taxonomy\n   196→\n   197→```\n   198→MCP Server Registry\n   199→├── Core (always available)\n   200→│   ├── filesystem — Read/write/search files in workspace"}]},"uuid":"963709a5-e1d0-4ee9-96ca-f42365910b0d","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:46:41.740Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"f33abff5-1200-4577-a7e4-44bf1280d3c4","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
