{"parentUuid":"5c9a0c94-7517-49d5-8c30-1e59f9826e99","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a8eaafaa5ba8f955e","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"callback"},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_015PZZdh27JyxB2PeABfgC2p","toolUseID":"toolu_015PZZdh27JyxB2PeABfgC2p","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:46:42.223Z","uuid":"319a1e4e-769f-4162-bb29-4f6d85713d91","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"f66b25d4-dccf-4f88-8aa4-eee3e67975de","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"74ab6cc1-259e-4f35-896b-31737bc09d28","agentId":"a8eaafaa5ba8f955e","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_015PZZdh27JyxB2PeABfgC2p","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# DHARMA SWARM: Router as Evolution Engine, Strange Loops & Attention Mechanism\n     2→## Deep Research Report — March 2026\n     3→\n     4→> Research compiled for the DHARMA SWARM project: a 7-layer self-evolving agentic swarm orchestrator built on a Gödel Machine-inspired architecture where layers can only modify downward and the top Dharma Layer is immutable.\n     5→\n     6→---\n     7→\n     8→## Table of Contents\n     9→\n    10→1. [Domain 1: Router as Self-Improving Evolution Engine](#domain-1)\n    11→   - 1A. Self-Improving Routing Policies\n    12→   - 1B. Training Routing Classifiers on Production Data\n    13→   - 1C. Automated Model Evaluation Pipelines\n    14→   - 1D. Evolutionary Search for Routing Configurations\n    15→2. [Domain 2: Strange Loops in Routing (Gödel Machine Pattern)](#domain-2)\n    16→   - 2A. Self-Referential Systems in AI\n    17→   - 2B. Router-Routing-Itself Scenarios\n    18→   - 2C. Safety Constraints on Self-Modification\n    19→3. [Domain 3: Router as Attention Mechanism / Resource Allocator](#domain-3)\n    20→   - 3A. Attention as Resource Allocation\n    21→   - 3B. Priority and Scheduling for LLM Workloads\n    22→   - 3C. Token Budget Allocation and Predictive Resource Allocation\n    23→4. [Synthesis: Implications for DHARMA SWARM](#synthesis)\n    24→\n    25→---\n    26→\n    27→<a name=\"domain-1\"></a>\n    28→## DOMAIN 1: Router as Self-Improving Evolution Engine\n    29→\n    30→### 1A. Self-Improving Routing Policies\n    31→\n    32→#### AlphaEvolve (Google DeepMind, 2025)\n    33→\n    34→AlphaEvolve is an evolutionary coding agent powered by Gemini models that discovers and optimizes algorithms through a population → evaluate → mutate → iterate loop. Its key architectural insight is directly applicable to routing: **the evaluator function is the key primitive**. If you can define a quantifiable routing quality metric (cost × quality × latency), AlphaEvolve can evolve routing heuristics as code.\n    35→\n    36→Core mechanism:\n    37→1. Start with candidate routing function (code)\n    38→2. Gemini Flash generates breadth of mutations; Gemini Pro provides depth on promising candidates\n    39→3. Automated evaluator scores each candidate routing function against production metrics\n    40→4. Evolutionary framework selects top performers and iterates\n    41→\n    42→**Already applied to scheduling:** AlphaEvolve discovered a heuristic for Google's Borg job scheduler that recovered **0.7% of worldwide compute resources** — a direct analogy to routing optimization. It also achieved a **23% speedup for the FlashAttention kernel** and is available via Google Cloud Early Access as of December 2025. [(Google DeepMind blog)](https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/) [(Ars Technica)](https://arstechnica.com/ai/2025/05/google-deepmind-creates-super-advanced-ai-that-can-invent-new-algorithms/)\n    43→\n    44→**Application to DHARMA routing:** The routing policy can be represented as a Python function: `def route(query: str, agent_context: dict, budget: float) -> ModelSelection`. AlphaEvolve can evolve this function continuously, with a private evaluator scoring routing decisions against quality/cost logs.\n    45→\n    46→#### Darwin Gödel Machine (Sakana AI + Jeff Clune Lab, May 2025)\n    47→\n    48→The DGM is the most concrete implementation of self-improving code relevant to DHARMA. It:\n    49→- Reads and modifies its own Python codebase\n    50→- Evaluates changes empirically on benchmarks (rather than requiring formal proofs)\n    51→- Maintains an **archive of diverse agents** (open-ended Darwinian search)\n    52→- Improved SWE-bench performance from **20.0% → 50.0%** autonomously\n    53→\n    54→The critical insight for routing: DGM separates self-modification from downstream performance. For DHARMA, the routing code IS the tool use and workflow — so the \"downstream task\" (quality responses at low cost) directly aligns with the \"self-improvement task\" (better routing code). This is the same alignment DGM found in coding tasks. [(arXiv:2505.22954)](https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.22954) [(Sakana AI)](https://sakana.ai/dgm/)\n    55→\n    56→**DGM's open-ended exploration finding:** Some ancestor agents that performed worse were instrumental in discovering breakthrough descendants. A pure hill-climbing router optimization would miss these. DHARMA's Darwin Engine must maintain routing policy diversity (not just optimize the current best policy).\n    57→\n    58→#### Huxley-Gödel Machine (Schmidhuber Lab, ICLR 2026)\n    59→\n    60→Published as an ICLR 2026 paper, the Huxley-GödelM machine formalizes a key concept: **Clade Meta-Productivity (CMP)** — measuring an agent's potential for self-improvement rather than just its current benchmark performance. This resolves the \"Metaproductivity-Performance Mismatch\": a routing policy that seems suboptimal *now* may have higher evolutionary potential.\n    61→\n    62→For DHARMA: when the Darwin Engine evaluates routing policy variants, it should score CMP (potential for future improvement) alongside immediate routing quality. [(arXiv:2510.21614)](https://arxiv.org/abs/2510.21614)\n    63→\n    64→#### ADAS — Automated Design of Agentic Systems (ICLR 2025)\n    65→\n    66→Published by Shengran Hu, Cong Lu, and Jeff Clune (UBC), ADAS defines the formal search space for automatically discovering agentic system designs. The **Meta Agent Search** algorithm:\n    67→- Uses a meta-agent to iteratively program new agents in code\n    68→- Evaluates on an archive of past discoveries\n    69→- Discovered agents outperform hand-designed SOTA agents on coding, science, and math\n    70→- Critically: **agents transfer robustly across domains and models**\n    71→\n    72→ADAS is directly applicable to routing policy design: the router itself can be in the code search space. The meta-agent can discover routing logic including prompts, tool use, workflow decisions, and multi-objective scoring functions. [(arXiv:2408.08435)](https://arxiv.org/abs/2408.08435) [(OpenReview ICLR 2025)](https://openreview.net/forum?id=t9U3LW7JVX)\n    73→\n    74→**ADAS search dimensions for routing:**\n    75→- Search Space: All possible routing functions (Turing-complete code space)\n    76→- Evaluation Function: Cost, latency, quality (multi-objective, configurable per DHARMA layer)\n    77→- ADAS does NOT directly focus on the routing layer specifically — but Meta Agent Search enables it as a component\n    78→\n    79→#### OpenELM (Apple, 2024)\n    80→\n    81→OpenELM is Apple's open-source efficient language model family with a **layer-wise scaling strategy** — smaller attention/FFN layers near the input, progressively larger near the output. This architecture relevance to routing: a layer-wise router that allocates heavier models to tasks requiring more complex reasoning mirrors OpenELM's principle of \"focus compute where it matters.\" OpenELM itself is NOT a self-evolving framework but demonstrates efficient parameter allocation as a design philosophy. [(Apple ML Research)](https://machinelearning.apple.com/research/openelm) [(arXiv:2404.14619)](https://arxiv.org/abs/2404.14619)\n    82→\n    83→#### Gödel Machine (Schmidhuber, 2003/2006) — Original Framework\n    84→\n    85→The Gödel Machine is a **provably globally optimal** self-improving system: it rewrites any part of its own code whenever it can formally prove the rewrite increases expected future utility. The challenge for routing: proving that a proposed routing policy change is net beneficial requires a formal model of the environment — tractable in bounded settings (e.g., a known model pool with measurable outputs) but intractable in general.\n    86→\n    87→**2026 status:** The Gödel Machine remains the theoretical ideal. The DGM and Huxley-GödelM are the practical approximations. For DHARMA's Darwin Engine, empirical validation (benchmark scores + production log analysis) replaces formal proofs — the DGM approach. The Gödel Machine principle of \"only accept provable improvements\" maps to DHARMA's constraint that modifications must prove utility against the Dharma Layer's immutable objectives.\n    88→\n    89→---\n    90→\n    91→### 1B. Training Routing Classifiers on Production Data\n    92→\n    93→#### RouteLLM: Training Framework\n    94→\n    95→RouteLLM (arXiv:2406.18665, last revised Feb 2025) is the canonical academic framework for training routing classifiers. Key facts:\n    96→\n    97→**Training data requirements:**\n    98→- Pairwise preference data (which of two model outputs is better)\n    99→- Can use Chatbot Arena data + LLM-as-judge augmentation\n   100→- Four architectures evaluated: SW-Ranking (cosine similarity), Matrix Factorization, BERT classifier, Causal LLM (Llama-3 8B)\n   101→- Matrix factorization is most cost-efficient; causal LLM has best performance\n   102→- Data augmentation with synthetic LLM-judge preferences substantially improves all routers\n   103→- Transfer learning: routers maintain performance **when the strong/weak models are swapped at test time** — critical for DHARMA where models change\n   104→\n   105→**Convergence:** RouteLLM reduces costs by **over 2× with no quality loss** on MT-Bench. The causal LLM router achieves 91% pass@1 on HumanEval routing. [(arXiv:2406.18665)](https://arxiv.org/abs/2406.18665)\n   106→\n   107→**Self-REF extension (ICML 2025):** Training LLMs with confidence tokens (Self-Reflection with Error-based Feedback) improves routing downstream by enabling models to signal their own uncertainty. The confidence token score predicts when to route upward to a stronger model — a self-referential element. [(ICML 2025 Poster)](https://icml.cc/virtual/2025/poster/45145)\n   108→\n   109→#### Not Diamond: Production Router Training\n   110→\n   111→Not Diamond is the leading production framework for custom router training. Pipeline:\n   112→\n   113→```python\n   114→# Minimum viable dataset: 15 samples; practical: 1000+; max: 10,000 per training job (5MB)\n   115→client = NotDiamond()\n   116→response = client.custom_router.train_custom_router(\n   117→    dataset_file=f,          # CSV: input prompt | model_response | score\n   118→    llm_providers=json.dumps(llm_providers),  # models to route between\n   119→    maximize=True,           # maximize the evaluation score\n   120→    prompt_column=\"Input\",\n   121→)\n   122→# Training time: minutes to 1 hour depending on dataset size\n   123→```\n   124→\n   125→Key insights:\n   126→- Training data = (prompt, response, score) triples — the DHARMA system should log all routing decisions + downstream quality scores automatically\n   127→- Supports retraining with `override=True` — the Darwin Engine can trigger periodic router retraining\n   128→- Custom models (fine-tuned variants) supported alongside standard providers\n   129→- Integration with W&B Weave for evaluation tracking and triggered retraining\n   130→\n   131→Reported gains: training custom routers with Not Diamond improves accuracy by **up to 25%** while reducing inference costs by **up to 10×**. [(Not Diamond docs)](https://docs.notdiamond.ai/docs/router-training-quickstart) [(W&B Weave guide)](https://wandb.ai/ml-reports/not-diamond/reports/How-to-train-an-LLM-router-with-W-B-Weave-and-Not-Diamond--VmlldzoxMDA0MjIwNA)\n   132→\n   133→#### Active Learning for Routing: Which Queries to Annotate\n   134→\n   135→The key insight: you cannot annotate everything. Active learning selects queries for annotation that maximize routing improvement per annotation dollar.\n   136→\n   137→**Best strategies for routing annotation (2025 research):**\n   138→1. **Uncertainty-based selection:** Annotate queries where the router's confidence is lowest — highest information gain\n   139→2. **Diversity-based selection (CoreSet):** Annotate queries maximally different from already-annotated ones — prevents distribution gaps\n   140→3. **Breaking Ties:** Select queries where top-2 model probabilities are closest — direct routing ambiguity\n   141→4. **Hybrid two-stage:** Cheap embedding model ranks by uncertainty → expensive LLM annotates top candidates\n   142→\n   143→**Online LLM Picker (OpenReview, Feb 2026):** Framework for active model selection in online settings with limited annotation budget. Processes a streaming query stream and selects the most informative prompts for annotation. Reduces annotation cost by **71.67%** while reliably identifying the best model. [(OpenReview, Feb 2026)](https://openreview.net/forum?id=R7uvPB8HHx)\n   144→\n   145→**PILOT (Adaptive LLM Routing under Budget Constraints, arXiv:2508.21141):** Preference-prior Informed LinUCB for Adaptive Routing. Key properties:\n   146→- Pretrains shared embedding space from offline human preference data (Chatbot Arena)\n   147→- Refines online via bandit feedback (only observing the reward of the chosen model)\n   148→- Online cost policy modeled as a **multi-choice knapsack problem** — enforces budget constraints\n   149→- Achieves 93% of GPT-4 performance at 25% of cost on RouterBench\n   150→- Routing overhead: **65ms** (Instructor-XL) vs. 2.5s GPT-4 inference — negligible\n   151→- Provably achieves smaller regret bound than standard bandit algorithms due to preference priors\n   152→\n   153→**For DHARMA bootstrapping:** Start with Chatbot Arena preference priors → deploy PILOT → log production feedback → trigger Not Diamond retraining every N queries. Annotation budget goes to the `Online LLM Picker` queries with highest uncertainty. [(arXiv:2508.21141)](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.21141v1)\n   154→\n   155→#### PILOT Convergence\n   156→\n   157→PILOT converges through the LinUCB regret bound framework: the algorithm's cumulative regret grows sublinearly (O(√T) or better), meaning the routing policy improves at a diminishing rate as more production feedback accumulates. In DHARMA's context: the router converges to near-optimal routing within a few thousand queries for each distinct agent type.\n   158→\n   159→---\n   160→\n   161→### 1C. Automated Model Evaluation Pipelines\n   162→\n   163→#### Shadow Traffic / Canary Evaluation\n   164→\n   165→The production-grade pattern for safely evaluating new models:\n   166→\n   167→**Shadow testing:**\n   168→1. Proxy/gateway intercepts production requests and duplicates them to a shadow model\n   169→2. Production model serves users; shadow model processes in parallel (async, never blocking production)\n   170→3. Shadow responses logged with metadata: timestamp, token count, model version\n   171→4. Evaluation scripts compare outputs: LLM-as-judge for quality, direct metrics for latency/cost\n   172→\n   173→**Canary rollout (after shadow validation):**\n   174→1. 1% → 5% → 10% → 50% → 100% traffic graduated shift\n   175→2. Feature flags enable instant rollback\n   176→3. Automated rollback triggers fire if: quality drops > threshold, error rate spikes, latency doubles\n   177→\n   178→**AWS SageMaker AI** provides managed shadow testing infrastructure. The shadow path must use async processing (Kafka/RabbitMQ) to never add latency to the production path. [(AWS docs)](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/sagemaker/latest/dg/shadow-tests.html) [(codeant.ai guide)](https://www.codeant.ai/blogs/shadow-traffic-llm-testing)\n   179→\n   180→**Agent drift detection (Maxim, Nov 2025):** Key metrics for detecting version drift in models:\n   181→- Token consumption per session (rising = over-exploration or verbose CoT)\n   182→- Tool selection accuracy (wrong selection rate)\n   183→- Trajectory stability (routing consistency across similar queries)\n   184→- Canary indexing + shadow traffic to validate new corpora before rollout\n   185→\n   186→[(Maxim agent drift guide)](https://www.getmaxim.ai/articles/managing-ai-agent-drift-how-to-maintain-consistent-performance-over-time/)\n   187→\n   188→#### LLM-as-Judge for Automatic Quality Scoring\n   189→\n   190→LLM-as-Judge achieves **~90% agreement with human judgments** (Frontiers study, 2025). For routing:\n   191→\n   192→**Three evaluation modes:**\n   193→1. **Pointwise:** Score each model response (1-5 on defined rubric)\n   194→2. **Pairwise:** Compare model A vs. model B for the same query\n   195→3. **Pass/Fail:** Binary quality gate\n   196→\n   197→**Contextual Evaluation Prompt Routing** (key innovation): Route *evaluation* queries themselves to different judge models based on query type — this is a meta-application of routing to evaluation, creating a self-referential evaluation loop. [(Frontiers, 2025)](https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/big-data/articles/10.3389/fdata.2025.1611389/full)\n   198→\n   199→**2025 evaluation landscape finding:** By late 2025, static benchmarks lost predictive power for production — MMLU scores above 80% became meaningless. The shift moved to dynamic, adversarial, expert-grounded evaluation. For DHARMA's router: the evaluation function itself must evolve as models improve. This is a recursive requirement — the evaluator of routing quality is itself subject to improvement by the Darwin Engine. [(Goodeye Labs 2025 review)](https://www.goodeyelabs.com/insights/llm-evaluation-2025-review)\n   200→"}]},"uuid":"ecc33f04-7be2-40f2-bc2c-c72098c822b4","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:46:42.223Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"f66b25d4-dccf-4f88-8aa4-eee3e67975de","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
