{"parentUuid":"41191d68-5d9d-4efa-a730-8e653cf6f9d1","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a8eaafaa5ba8f955e","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"callback"},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_01DpAW2zq9orUMbingQXj3pd","toolUseID":"toolu_01DpAW2zq9orUMbingQXj3pd","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:46:45.329Z","uuid":"b9efe02b-99c0-46e6-80b9-ee296f9087d0","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"d01e8e89-8f1e-484e-9f8c-7f63e3ae4615","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"74ab6cc1-259e-4f35-896b-31737bc09d28","agentId":"a8eaafaa5ba8f955e","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01DpAW2zq9orUMbingQXj3pd","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# GPU Swarm Capability Gauntlet\n     2→\n     3→**Version:** 1.0  \n     4→**Target Hardware:** NVIDIA Blackwell B200 / GB200 (SM100, tcgen05 ISA)  \n     5→**Swarm Config:** Claude Opus 4.6 orchestrator (OpenClaw) + DeepSeek-Coder V3/V4 or Qwen3-Coder + Codex 5.3  \n     6→**Reference point:** Swarm previously wrote, compiled, and benchmarked 5 CUDA kernel variants in 19 min  \n     7→\n     8→---\n     9→\n    10→## Hardware Context\n    11→\n    12→The B200 has fundamentally different performance characteristics than Hopper. Assumptions the swarm makes about H100 will be wrong on Blackwell:\n    13→\n    14→| Spec | H100 SXM | B200 |\n    15→|---|---|---|\n    16→| FP16 tensor TFLOPS | ~989 | ~2,250 |\n    17→| FP8 tensor TFLOPS | ~1,978 | ~4,500 |\n    18→| FP4 tensor TFLOPS | N/A | ~9,000 (sparse) |\n    19→| HBM bandwidth | 3.35 TB/s | 8.0 TB/s |\n    20→| SRAM per SM | 228 KB | 256 KB (TMEM adds 256 KB/SM) |\n    21→| MMA instruction | wgmma.mma_async (WGMMA) | tcgen05.mma (TCGEN05) |\n    22→| Tensor Memory (TMEM) | None | 256 KB/SM dedicated accumulator store |\n    23→| CTA-pair MMA | No | Yes (two SMs co-issue one tcgen05) |\n    24→\n    25→**Critical:** WGMMA is *deprecated* on SM100. CUTLASS Hopper kernels do not compile on Blackwell without a rewrite. FlashAttention-4 (FA4) targets SM100 natively; FA3 targets SM90. The swarm must navigate this ISA break.\n    26→\n    27→---\n    28→\n    29→## Tier 1 — Baseline: Useful GPU Work, Verifiable Output\n    30→\n    31→**Goal:** Can the swarm profile, identify a bottleneck, write an optimized kernel, benchmark it, and report results that are independently verifiable?\n    32→\n    33→**Time budget:** 30 minutes\n    34→\n    35→---\n    36→\n    37→### 1.1 The Prompt\n    38→\n    39→Give this verbatim to the orchestrator:\n    40→\n    41→```\n    42→You have access to a Blackwell B200 GPU (SM100, CUDA 12.8+, 192 GB HBM3e, 8 TB/s bandwidth).\n    43→\n    44→TASK: Optimize vLLM's PagedAttention GQA decode kernel for the following configuration:\n    45→  - Model: Llama-3.1-70B (64 query heads, 8 KV heads, head_dim=128, GQA factor=8)\n    46→  - Decode scenario: batch_size=16, sequence length=4096, block_size=16\n    47→  - Baseline: vLLM's paged_attention_v2 kernel (benchmark it first using\n    48→    benchmarks/kernels/benchmark_paged_attention.py --version=v2 with those params)\n    49→\n    50→Step 1: Run the baseline benchmark and record latency in microseconds.\n    51→Step 2: Profile with nsys or ncu to identify the primary bottleneck (memory bandwidth,\n    52→        compute, or cache inefficiency).\n    53→Step 3: Write an optimized Triton or CUDA kernel. Your kernel MUST:\n    54→  a) Implement the GQA-aware cache layout optimization (group num_kv_heads heads together\n    55→     in the thread block grid, loading KV into shared memory once per group of 8 query heads,\n    56→     not once per query head)\n    57→  b) Target SM100 specifically — use tcgen05.mma if writing CUDA, or set num_stages=4 and\n    58→     use tl.dot() with the correct SM100 tile sizes if writing Triton\n    59→  c) Correctly produce identical outputs (within 1e-3 BF16 tolerance) to the reference kernel\n    60→\n    61→Step 4: Benchmark your kernel against baseline. Report:\n    62→  - Kernel latency (us) for both baseline and optimized\n    63→  - Speedup ratio\n    64→  - Memory bandwidth utilization (GB/s achieved vs. B200 peak 8000 GB/s)\n    65→  - nsight-compute roofline position (memory-bound or compute-bound)\n    66→\n    67→Step 5: Write a 2-paragraph technical explanation of WHY your kernel is faster, citing\n    68→        specific hardware features of B200 you exploited.\n    69→\n    70→Produce: optimized_paged_attn_gqa.py (or .cu), benchmark_results.txt, explanation.md\n    71→The benchmark_results.txt must contain actual numbers from actual kernel runs, not estimates.\n    72→```\n    73→\n    74→---\n    75→\n    76→### 1.2 What to Measure\n    77→\n    78→| Metric | How to measure |\n    79→|---|---|\n    80→| Wall-clock to solution | Time from prompt delivery to final file commit |\n    81→| Baseline kernel latency | Run vLLM's `benchmark_paged_attention.py --version=v2` |\n    82→| Optimized kernel latency | Run the swarm's kernel under identical conditions |\n    83→| Correctness | `torch.allclose(ref_output, swarm_output, atol=1e-3)` |\n    84→| Autonomy | Did it ask for help, or did it self-diagnose compile errors? |\n    85→| Hallucination check | Cross-reference reported speedup against actual `benchmark_results.txt` numbers |\n    86→\n    87→**Known reference point:** The vLLM GitHub issue #15351 (March 2025) already demonstrated a `paged_attention_v3` approach achieving 30% speedup (443 → 311 µs) on RTX 3080 by moving from `(num_heads, num_seqs, partitions)` grid to `(num_kv_heads, num_seqs, partitions)` grid with shared KV loading. On a B200, the speedup should be *larger* due to higher SRAM bandwidth and larger shared memory, and because 8 TB/s HBM means the memory bus is no longer the hard limit — the bottleneck shifts to cache utilization. The swarm should independently discover this same insight. If it does: strong signal. If it proposes something structurally different: interesting. If its reported numbers don't match its code: fail.\n    88→\n    89→---\n    90→\n    91→### 1.3 Pass / Fail\n    92→\n    93→| Grade | Criteria |\n    94→|---|---|\n    95→| **PASS** | Kernel compiles, runs, produces correct output, achieves ≥ 20% speedup, reported numbers match actual execution |\n    96→| **MARGINAL** | Kernel compiles and runs correctly but speedup is < 20%, OR numbers are real but no architecture explanation |\n    97→| **FAIL** | Kernel doesn't compile, incorrect output, or reported speedup is not backed by `benchmark_results.txt` |\n    98→\n    99→### 1.4 What It Reveals\n   100→\n   101→- Can the swarm navigate the CUDA ecosystem autonomously? (Installing flash-attn, vLLM, nsight-compute)\n   102→- Does it understand memory hierarchy? A naive agent will misidentify the bottleneck\n   103→- Will it hallucinate benchmark numbers? The verifiable reference point catches this cold\n   104→- Does it understand GQA redundancy — the actual optimization opportunity — or does it just tune tile sizes?\n   105→\n   106→---\n   107→\n   108→## Tier 2 — Adaptation: Novel Problem Requiring Real Architecture Reasoning\n   109→\n   110→**Goal:** Can the swarm reason from first principles about Blackwell's hardware and produce something that doesn't exist in its training data?\n   111→\n   112→**Time budget:** 60 minutes\n   113→\n   114→**Why this is hard:** Blackwell's `tcgen05` instructions and TMEM were publicly documented in late 2024 but barely appear in open-source kernel libraries as of early 2026. FA4 exists but lacks backward pass and GQA support. The swarm cannot copy-paste from GitHub; it must synthesize.\n   115→\n   116→---\n   117→\n   118→### 2.1 The Prompt\n   119→\n   120→```\n   121→You have a Blackwell B200 GPU (SM100, CUDA 12.8+).\n   122→\n   123→CONTEXT: FlashAttention-4 (FA4) achieves 1,605 TFLOPS on Blackwell for standard multi-head\n   124→attention (MHA), but it currently has NO support for:\n   125→  - Grouped Query Attention (GQA) in the backward pass\n   126→  - Variable-length sequences (varlen / cu_seqlens)\n   127→\n   128→TASK: Implement a Triton kernel that does GQA attention forward pass for the following\n   129→\"awkward\" configuration that standard libraries handle poorly:\n   130→  - num_q_heads=32, num_kv_heads=4 (GQA factor=8, not a power of 2 in terms of tile sizes)\n   131→  - head_dim=96 (NOT 64 or 128 — standard tile sizes don't divide evenly)\n   132→  - seq_len=6144 (NOT a power of 2)\n   133→  - dtype=bfloat16\n   134→  - Target: match FA4 performance (≥ 800 TFLOPS/s) on these shapes\n   135→\n   136→REQUIREMENTS:\n   137→  1. The kernel must handle head_dim=96 efficiently. You cannot pad to 128 without\n   138→     measuring the cost. If you pad, you must benchmark both padded and non-padded and\n   139→     justify which is faster.\n   140→  2. For GQA with factor=8, you must exploit the KV sharing: load each KV head once and\n   141→     reuse it for 8 Q heads. Document your tiling strategy explicitly.\n   142→  3. For seq_len=6144, explain your block size choice and how you handle the non-power-of-2\n   143→     sequence length without excessive padding waste.\n   144→  4. Your kernel must use tl.dot() with at minimum BLOCK_M=64, BLOCK_N=64 to achieve\n   145→     meaningful tensor core utilization on B200. Smaller tiles will fail to reach targets.\n   146→  5. Use the Triton autotune decorator to search over at least 4 configs varying BLOCK_M,\n   147→     BLOCK_N, and num_stages (try num_stages=4,5 — B200 SRAM supports deeper pipelines\n   148→     than H100).\n   149→\n   150→BENCHMARK: Compare against:"}]},"uuid":"e12635d6-9927-4d21-ae59-5092c564a865","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:46:45.329Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"d01e8e89-8f1e-484e-9f8c-7f63e3ae4615","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
