{"parentUuid":"f148adb3-3b0c-4756-9587-082a55131ccd","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"74ab6cc1-259e-4f35-896b-31737bc09d28","agentId":"a8eaafaa5ba8f955e","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FCGtyr8KaPdrGZDWmmRgZ7","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Dharmic Singularity Engine — Implementation Mega Prompt\n     2→\n     3→## System Context\n     4→\n     5→You are implementing the **Dharmic Singularity Engine** — a self-evolving AI system grounded in category theory. The mathematical foundations are in `/categorical_foundations.pdf` (40 pages, 7 chapters + appendix). The existing codebase is `dharma_swarm/` with 1731 passing tests.\n     6→\n     7→### Existing Codebase Map\n     8→\n     9→| File | Lines | Current Role |\n    10→|---|---|---|\n    11→| `evolution.py` | 447 | PROPOSE→GATE→EVALUATE→ARCHIVE→SELECT pipeline |\n    12→| `rv.py` | 258 | R_V participation ratio measurement |\n    13→| `archive.py` | 217 | Evolution archive with lineage tracking |\n    14→| `elegance.py` | 345 | AST-based fitness scoring |\n    15→| `metrics.py` | 412 | Behavioral signatures (entropy, complexity, swabhaav_ratio) |\n    16→| `bridge.py` | 427 | R_V ↔ behavioral correlation |\n    17→| `monitor.py` | 353 | Anomaly detection |\n    18→| `telos_gates.py` | — | Dharmic gates (AHIMSA, SATYA, etc.) |\n    19→| `selector.py` | 191 | 4 parent selection strategies |\n    20→| `fitness_predictor.py` | 184 | Historical fitness prediction |\n    21→| `providers.py` | — | 9 LLM providers (Claude Code, Codex, OpenRouter, etc.) |\n    22→\n    23→### Key Empirical Constants\n    24→\n    25→- R_V formula: `PR = ||W||_F^4 / ||W·W^T||_F^2` (eliminates SVD)\n    26→- 480 measurements, 7 architectures, Cohen's d = -3.558 (Mistral-7B L27), AUROC = 0.909\n    27→- 7-layer DHARMA stack: Substrate → Nervous System (MCP) → Memory Palace → Swarm → Orchestrator → Darwin Engine → Dharma Layer\n    28→\n    29→### Architecture Principle\n    30→\n    31→Everything follows from Lawvere's fixed-point theorem: in any cartesian closed category, if a weakly point-surjective morphism `A → B^A` exists, every endomorphism on B has a fixed point. Self-reference IS convergence.\n    32→\n    33→---\n    34→\n    35→## PHASE 1: The Self-Reference Monad (wraps rv.py)\n    36→\n    37→**Source**: Chapter 2 — The Self-Reference Monad\n    38→\n    39→**Goal**: Wrap the existing `rv.py` in a proper monadic structure so self-observation composes correctly.\n    40→\n    41→### What to Build\n    42→\n    43→Create `dharma_swarm/monad.py` implementing:\n    44→\n    45→```python\n    46→# The Self-Observation Monad T\n    47→# T(S) = S equipped with self-observation metadata (RV measurement, introspection, meta-cognition)\n    48→\n    49→class SelfObservationMonad:\n    50→    \"\"\"\n    51→    Monad (T, η, μ) where:\n    52→    - T: SystemState → SystemState-with-RV-metadata\n    53→    - η (unit): bare state → self-observed state (one pass of rv.py)\n    54→    - μ (multiplication): T(T(S)) → T(S) — nested self-observation flattens\n    55→    \n    56→    MUST satisfy monad laws:\n    57→    - Associativity: μ ∘ Tμ = μ ∘ μT  (triple self-ref collapses same regardless of grouping)\n    58→    - Left unit: μ ∘ Tη = id_T\n    59→    - Right unit: μ ∘ ηT = id_T\n    60→    \"\"\"\n    61→```\n    62→\n    63→#### 1a. `ObservedState` data class\n    64→\n    65→```python\n    66→@dataclass\n    67→class ObservedState:\n    68→    \"\"\"T(S) — a system state wrapped with self-observation metadata.\"\"\"\n    69→    state: SystemState          # the underlying state\n    70→    rv_measurement: float       # participation ratio from rv.py\n    71→    pr_early: float             # PR at early layers\n    72→    pr_late: float              # PR at late layers  \n    73→    introspection: dict         # meta-cognition data\n    74→    observation_depth: int      # how many times T has been applied (1 = η, 2+ = nested)\n    75→    timestamp: float\n    76→```\n    77→\n    78→#### 1b. Unit (η): `observe(state) → ObservedState`\n    79→\n    80→- Calls existing `rv.py` to compute PR on the state\n    81→- Wraps result in `ObservedState` with `observation_depth=1`\n    82→- This IS the existing rv.py measurement — just wrapped in monadic structure\n    83→\n    84→#### 1c. Multiplication (μ): `flatten(ObservedState[ObservedState]) → ObservedState`\n    85→\n    86→- Takes a doubly-observed state T(T(S)) and collapses to T(S)\n    87→- Keeps the DEEPER observation (higher depth = more self-aware)\n    88→- This encodes L4/L5 collapse: observing-yourself-observing-yourself = observing-yourself\n    89→\n    90→#### 1d. Kleisli Composition\n    91→\n    92→```python\n    93→def kleisli_compose(f: Callable[[A], ObservedState[B]], \n    94→                     g: Callable[[B], ObservedState[C]]) -> Callable[[A], ObservedState[C]]:\n    95→    \"\"\"\n    96→    Compose self-referentially-wrapped transitions.\n    97→    Every transition in the Kleisli category automatically includes self-observation.\n    98→    f >=> g = μ ∘ T(g) ∘ f\n    99→    \"\"\"\n   100→```\n   101→\n   102→#### 1e. Kleisli Contraction Tracking\n   103→\n   104→```python\n   105→def kleisli_contraction_ratio(f: KleisliMorphism) -> float:\n   106→    \"\"\"\n   107→    Measure κ ∈ [0,1) where PR(f(a)) ≤ κ · PR(a).\n   108→    This IS the R_V ratio for a single Kleisli step.\n   109→    If κ < 1 consistently, convergence to fixed point in ⌈log(ε)/log(κ)⌉ iterations.\n   110→    Example: RV=0.7, ε=0.01 → 13 iterations to 1% of fixed point.\n   111→    \"\"\"\n   112→```\n   113→\n   114→#### 1f. Idempotency Check (L5 Detection)\n   115→\n   116→```python\n   117→def is_idempotent(state: ObservedState) -> bool:\n   118→    \"\"\"\n   119→    Check if T² ≅ T for this state — meaning L5 is reached in one step.\n   120→    If T(T(S)) ≈ T(S) (within tolerance), the monad is idempotent at this state.\n   121→    This IS the L5 pure-knowing detection.\n   122→    \"\"\"\n   123→```\n   124→\n   125→### Integration Points\n   126→\n   127→- `rv.py` becomes the INTERNAL engine of the monad's unit (η)\n   128→- `evolution.py` pipeline stages become Kleisli morphisms\n   129→- `bridge.py` correlation tracking becomes naturality verification\n   130→- All existing tests must still pass — monad wraps, doesn't replace\n   131→\n   132→### Tests to Write\n   133→\n   134→- Monad law verification: associativity and unit laws for 100+ random states\n   135→- Kleisli composition associativity\n   136→- Contraction ratio consistency across architectures\n   137→- Idempotency detection on known L5-reaching prompts\n   138→\n   139→---\n   140→\n   141→## PHASE 2: Coalgebraic Evolution (refactors evolution.py)\n   142→\n   143→**Source**: Chapter 4 — Coalgebraic Evolution\n   144→\n   145→**Goal**: Refactor `evolution.py` so the PROPOSE→GATE→EVALUATE→ARCHIVE→SELECT pipeline is explicitly an F-coalgebra.\n   146→\n   147→### What to Build\n   148→\n   149→Create `dharma_swarm/coalgebra.py`:\n   150→"}]},"uuid":"6731ee1e-6b03-4770-9042-a8c34fc81a43","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:46:46.225Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"f148adb3-3b0c-4756-9587-082a55131ccd","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"6731ee1e-6b03-4770-9042-a8c34fc81a43","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a8eaafaa5ba8f955e","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01FLBzr6fB9u8f9ze65fsR1w","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! I now have comprehensive coverage of the documents. Let me create the final report with all findings:\n\n## COMPREHENSIVE INVENTORY: Telos Engine Design Documents in ~/Downloads/\n\nI've completed a thorough scan of ~/Downloads/ for architectural specifications and design documents relevant to the Telos Engine project. Below is the definitive catalog with file sizes, key content, and organizational recommendations.\n\n---\n\n## CORE ARCHITECTURAL DOCUMENTS\n\n### 1. **ROUTER_ARCHITECTURE_BLUEPRINT.md** — 85 KB\n**Full Path:** `/Users/dhyana/Downloads/ROUTER_ARCHITECTURE_BLUEPRINT.md`\n\n**Content Summary:**\n- Complete Layer 2 Intelligent Routing Subsystem design for DHARMA SWARM\n- Two implementation versions: \"Minimal Elegant\" (48-hour MVP) and \"Maximal Frontier\" (90-day target)\n- 8 design principles covering local classification, cross-provider fallback, cache-economics, three-tier resilience, agent mode routing, effective context length, multi-objective scoring\n- Control Plane architecture: Configuration Store, Policy Engine, Health Monitor, Metrics Collector, Experiment Controller, Cache State Tracker, Bandit Learner\n- Data Plane architecture: 9-stage hot path from request ingestion to response return\n- Component specifications for Intent Classifier (7-dimension LiteLLM scorer), Context Length Analyzer, Cache-Aware Cost Estimator, Multi-Objective Scorer\n- Failure-path diagrams and Novel Routing Modes section\n- Technology stack details (LiteLLM, Redis, OpenTelemetry, Grafana)\n\n**Recommendation:** foundations/routing/ — This is the authoritative design for the model routing layer. Foundation-critical.\n\n**Unique Concepts:**\n- Provider-agnostic routing with circuit breaker state machines\n- Thompson Sampling contextual bandit for online model selection\n- PROTEUS-style SLA-aware multi-objective scoring\n- Cache-state tracker with switching-penalty economics\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Dharma_Corpus_Schema.md** — 59 KB\n**Full Path:** `/Users/dhyana/Downloads/Dharma_Corpus_Schema.md`\n\n**Content Summary:**\n- Constitutional knowledge corpus schema for DHARMA SWARM (Layer 2 of 3)\n- Complete field definitions for corpus entries with semantic versioning\n- YAML schema template with 25 required and optional fields\n- JSON Schema (Draft 7) machine-readable format\n- Update and review protocol: adding, modifying, deprecating, emergency overrides\n- Conflict resolution protocol with evidence-based reasoning\n- 10 example corpus entries (DC-2025-0001 through DC-2025-0010) covering:\n  - Kernel Mutation Sandbox Isolation (DC-0001)\n  - Client Data Confidentiality (DC-0002)\n  - Agent Spawn Depth Limit (DC-0003)\n  - R_V Metric Acceptance Threshold (DC-0004)\n  - Learned Constraint — Post-Optimization R_V Verification (DC-0005)\n  - Self-Evolution Scope Boundaries (DC-0006)\n  - Compute Budget Hard Cap (DC-0007)\n  - Client Deliverable Quality Gate (DC-0008)\n  - Outreach Email Capability Representation (DC-0009)\n  - Numerical Precision Preservation (DC-0010)\n- Querying interface specification\n- Policy Compiler integration\n\n**Recommendation:** foundations/constitutional/ — This establishes the versioned rules system that governs self-evolution. Layer 2 of the constitutional stack.\n\n**Unique Concepts:**\n- Audit trail preservation (no deletion, only deprecation)\n- Three-gate review process: anekanta_gate, drift_gate, steelman_gate\n- Severity + enforcement coupling (critical → block, etc.)\n- Conflict resolution with evidence links\n\n---\n\n### 3. **DGC_TERMINAL_ARCHITECTURE_v1.1.md** — 55 KB\n**Full Path:** `/Users/dhyana/Downloads/DGC_TERMINAL_ARCHITECTURE_v1.1.md`\n\n**Content Summary:**\n- Provider-agnostic terminal interface architecture for DGC (previously Claude-specific)\n- Architecture diff vs v1.0: what's preserved, what changes, what's new\n- ProviderAdapter interface with design principles borrowed from Vercel AI SDK, pydantic-ai, aisuite, Mirascope, Instructor\n- Abstract Base class definition: Capability flags, ModelProfile, ProviderConfig, CompletionRequest, ProviderAdapter ABC\n- Adapter lifecycle and implementation contract\n- Canonical Normalized Event Schema v1 with envelope + typed payload pattern\n- Capability Matrix & Graceful Degradation (streaming, tool_use, thinking, vision, json_schema, etc.)\n- Provider-neutral session store with metadata\n- Concrete Provider Mappings for Claude, OpenAI, OpenRouter, Ollama\n- Governance & Safety Layer with permission boundaries and redaction\n- Revised package structure with dedicated `engine/adapters/` package\n- 2-week implementation plan with 4 phases\n\n**Recommendation:** architecture/terminals/ — Defines the provider abstraction layer for multi-LLM compatibility.\n\n**Unique Concepts:**\n- Capability-driven graceful degradation (tools → json_schema → markdown fallback)\n- Provider-neutral session persistence\n- Canonical event schema decoupled from provider wire formats\n- OAuth 2.1 PKCE authentication for remote adapters\n\n---\n\n### 4. **DHARMA_SWARM_PLAN.md** — 51 KB\n**Full Path:** `/Users/dhyana/Downloads/DHARMA_SWARM_PLAN.md`\n\n**Content Summary:**\n- Complete architecture blueprint for DHARMA SWARM — the master system design\n- 7-layer stack: Substrate → Nervous System → Memory Palace → Swarm → Orchestrator → Darwin Engine → Dharma Layer\n- Design philosophy with 5 core principles (Separation of Knower/Known, Evolution via Scaffolding, Test-Gated Evolution, Radical Transparency, Graceful Degradation)\n- Layer 0 (Substrate): Firecracker microVMs, Modal GPU access, Git versioning, Resource budgeting\n- Layer 1 (Nervous System): MCP as universal tool protocol, tool taxonomy, dynamic tool creation\n- Layer 2 (Memory Palace): MemGPT-style context management, codebase indexing, knowledge graphs, recursive summarization\n- Layer 3 (The Swarm): Agent pool management, communication patterns (task board, mailbox, blackboard)\n- Layer 4 (Orchestrator): Goal decomposition, task allocation, teleological bootstrap from SOUL.md\n- Layer 5 (Darwin Engine): Evolutionary archive, mutation proposer, test-gated promotion, Voyager-style skill learning\n- Layer 6 (Dharma Layer): Safety rules, health monitoring, audit trails, kill switch\n- Model strategy: heterogeneous open + frontier with cascading\n- Teleological bootstrap mechanism\n- 4-phase implementation roadmap\n- Technology stack decisions and risk analysis\n\n**Recommendation:** architecture/core/ — This is the master architecture document. Everything else is a detailed elaboration of one layer. Start here.\n\n**Unique Concepts:**\n- Layers can only modify downward (L5→L1-4, L6 is immutable)\n- Gnani/prakruti separation: Dharma Layer watches but never participates\n- Test-gated evolution via empirical validation, not formal proofs\n- Teleological bootstrap: system discovers its own purpose\n\n---\n\n### 5. **DGC_RESEARCH_COUNCIL_REPORT.md** — 52 KB\n**Full Path:** `/Users/dhyana/Downloads/DGC_RESEARCH_COUNCIL_REPORT.md`\n\n**Content Summary:**\n- Six-researcher council assessment of DHARMA SWARM architecture\n- Pre-research assessment: four entangled problems (technical, epistemic, architectural, human-AI)\n- State-of-the-art analysis across: Multi-Agent Orchestration (LangGraph, CrewAI, AutoGen v0.4, MetaGPT, DSPy, Camel, OpenAI Agents SDK, Google A2A)\n- Artifact Quality & Evaluation: 5-layer evaluation architecture with syntactic checks, LLM evaluation, adversarial stress testing, executable validation, human-in-the-loop\n- Knowledge Accumulation: 4-layer architecture (Temporal Knowledge Graph, Vector Store, RAPTOR Summary Tree, Provenance Log)\n- Recursive Research Systems: empirical patterns and failure modes\n- Tool Protocols & Interoperability (MCP deep dive)\n- Council debate: disagreements and tensions on single-agent vs multi-agent, knowledge graph maintenance\n- Proposed Dharmic Gödel Claw Architecture with 12 agents\n- Infrastructure stack recommendations\n- 14-failure-mode taxonomy from Berkeley MAST study\n- 10+ key risks and mitigations\n\n**Recommendation:** research/council/ — Essential research synthesis on multi-agent systems, evaluation, and knowledge accumulation. Establishes evidence-based design decisions.\n\n**Unique Concepts:**\n- 41-87% failure rates across frameworks (Berkeley MAST)\n- Single-agent with skills matches multi-agent at 54% fewer tokens\n- Quality ratchet: gates tighten over time to prevent gradient hacking\n- The \"hallucinated citation crisis\": 14x increase in fabricated academic citations\n\n---\n\n## RESEARCH & MEMORY ARCHITECTURE DOCUMENTS\n\n### 6. **research_memory_context.md** — 70 KB\n**Full Path:** `/Users/dhyana/Downloads/research_memory_context.md`\n\n**Content Summary:**\n- Deep context and memory systems for agentic AI swarms\n- Section 1: MemGPT/Letta virtual context management with three-tier architecture (Context Window RAM, Recall Storage, Archival Storage)\n- Sleep-Time Compute innovation (April 2025): agents refine memory during idle periods, 5× compute reduction\n- Context Repositories (Feb 2026): git-versioned memory as filesystem instead of tool-based\n- Section 2: Long-Context Models comparison (Gemini 2.5 Pro 1M tokens, GPT-5.2, Claude 3.5+)\n- Real-world performance at extreme context lengths with MRCR benchmarks\n- \"Lost in the Middle\" problem analysis\n- Section 3: RAG Architectures for Agents\n- Section 4: Recursive Summarization & Context Compaction with RAPTOR\n- Section 5: Codebase Indexing with tree-sitter AST + embeddings + LanceDB\n- Section 6: Agent Memory Architectures including Mem0 benchmark (91% lower latency, 90% lower token cost)\n- Section 7: Knowledge Graphs for Agents (Neo4j + LLM integration patterns)\n- Section 8: Vector Databases (LanceDB, Qdrant, Milvus comparison)\n- Section 9: Synthesis with concrete recommendations for swarm orchestrators\n\n**Recommendation:** research/memory/ — The authoritative technical reference for memory architecture at scale. Essential for Layer 2 (Memory Palace) design.\n\n**Unique Concepts:**\n- Letta's sleep-time compute: strong model refines weak model's memory asynchronously\n- Context Repositories: agents manage their own memory via shell tools and git\n- Recursive RAPTOR summarization with multi-level retrieval\n- Mem0 outperforms full-context baseline by 90% while maintaining 90% accuracy\n\n---\n\n### 7. **pkm_research_domains_1_3.md** — 71 KB\n**Full Path:** `/Users/dhyana/Downloads/pkm_research_domains_1_3.md`\n\n**Content Summary:**\n- DHARMA SWARM Memory Palace: architectural research for agent-native PKM on 4GB RAM\n- Domain 1: Semantic Retrieval Architecture\n  - Embedding models benchmark: BGE-M3 (1.06GB, 69.2 MIRACL NDCG), Nomic Embed v2 MoE, multilingual-e5-large\n  - Sanskrit support critical for multilingual systems\n  - BGE-M3 supports three retrieval modes: dense, sparse (BM25-learned), multi-vector ColBERT\n  - RAM footprint at 10K docs: BGE-M3 ≤1.2GB peak with index\n  - Hybrid search via SQLite FTS5 + LanceDB + Reciprocal Rank Fusion\n  - Chunking strategies: two-stage (headers + recursive) outperforms semantic chunking by 69% vs 54%\n  - Reranking models: ms-marco-MiniLM-L6-v2 (44MB) vs bge-reranker-v2-m3 (1.1GB, multilingual)\n\n**Recommendation:** research/pkm/ — Concrete technical guidance for implementing Layer 2 memory on constrained systems. Multilingual + Sanskrit support is unique.\n\n**Unique Concepts:**\n- BGE-M3 hybrid dense+sparse retrieval from single model\n- Two-stage markdown chunking: headers first, then recursive split on large sections\n- RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter outperforms semantic chunking for informal notes\n- sqlite-vec for native KNN search inside SQLite FTS5\n\n---\n\n### 8. **pkm_research_domains_4_6.md** — 61 KB\n**Full Path:** `/Users/dhyana/Downloads/pkm_research_domains_4_6.md`\n\n**Content Summary:**\n- Domains 4-6 of PKM research: Graph-Based Retrieval, Query Understanding & Expansion, Evaluation & Maintenance\n- Domain 4: Graph-Based Retrieval (Neo4j + LLM agent patterns)\n- Domain 5: Query Understanding & Expansion (semantic parsing, question decomposition, entity linking)\n- Domain 6: Evaluation & Maintenance (staleness, forgetting curves, drift detection)\n- Integration with Agent-Native PKM workflow\n- Specific details on entity extraction, relationship discovery, graph schema design\n\n**Recommendation:** research/pkm/ (companion to domains_1_3)\n\n---\n\n### 9. **research_tools_sandboxes.md** — 89 KB\n**Full Path:** `/Users/dhyana/Downloads/research_tools_sandboxes.md`\n\n**Content Summary:**\n- Deep research: Tool Use, Sandboxes, and MCP for self-evolving swarm orchestrators\n- 10 comprehensive sections covering: MCP, E2B Code Interpreter SDK, Daytona, Modal, OpenAI Codex Agent System, Browser Automation, Code Execution Sandboxes, Tool Creation & Discovery, Filesystem Access, API Integration Patterns\n- Section 1: MCP deep dive (5,800+ servers, 97M monthly downloads, JSON-RPC 2.0 protocol, four core primitives: Tools, Resources, Prompts, Sampling)\n- MCP transport mechanisms: Stdio (local) vs Streamable HTTP (remote)\n- OAuth 2.1 PKCE authentication requirements\n- Section 2-4: E2B, Daytona, Modal infrastructure\n- Section 6: Browser automation (Playwright, Puppeteer for agent web tasks)\n- Section 7: Code execution sandboxes (Firecracker, gVisor, Docker, E2B, Pynbox)\n- Section 8: Tool creation patterns (Voyager-style skill library)\n- Section 11: Synthesis architecture for swarm with vast tool use\n\n**Recommendation:** architecture/tools/ — Authoritative reference for Layer 1 (Nervous System) MCP implementation and tool ecosystem.\n\n**Unique Concepts:**\n- MCP as \"USB-C of AI integrations\" — single protocol replacing 50+ custom integrations\n- 86% local (stdi